<FIRST>r a AM-StringfellowToxics     06-03 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stringfellow Toxics,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury: California Must Share Cost of Stringfellow Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of California should share the huge
cost of cleaning up the Stringfellow toxic waste site, a project
with a potential price tag of up to $740 million, a jury decided
Friday.
   The six-member federal jury did not determine how much the state
should contribute to the cleanup of the Riverside County hazardous
waste site, leaving that decision to U.S. District Court Judge
James Ideman.
   The decision came after less than a day of deliberations.
   The Stringfellow site opened in 1956 and received an estimated
34 million gallons of acids, pesticides and other toxic materials
before it was closed in 1972.
   The panel ruled the state was liable because it supervised
construction of the toxic landfill, delayed cleanup activities and
allowed a dangerous condition to exist on public property.
   The jurors also found the state liable for maintaining a
nuisance and breaching its duty to deal with toxic contamination,
but ruled the state was not negligent in choosing or designing the
site in the early 1950s, or for failing to remedy the toxic
contamination.
   The decision pleased lawyers for J.B. Stringfellow Jr., owner of
the quarry that contained the dump and 14 users of the landfill who
were all found liable to share cleanup costs by Ideman.
   ``We believe the implications of today's ruling is that the
state will bear the lion's share,'' said attorney Michael Kahn.
   Stringfellow, 62, of Costa Mesa said he was delighted with the
jury's decision. ``I feel better,'' he said. ``It's the first time
anyone had heard my story.''
   Deputy Attorney General Don Robinson said the verdict favored
the state because it rejected the plaintiffs' claims the state was
negligent in choosing and designing the dumpsite, and that it
allegedly failed to remedy problems that became apparent in the
1970s.
   Robinson hinted that an appeal was possible, saying that he felt
the jury would not have found the state liable at all if retired
judge Harry Peetris, who presided over the fact-finding hearing,
had not refused to instruct the jury on several legal defenses
possibly applicable to the state.
   ``It is the opinion of the attorney general's office that these
defenses would have barred any finding of liability against the
state on the portion of the verdict that dealt with those
theories,'' Robinson said.
   During the two-month proceeding, Deputy Attorney General Barbara
Noble told the jury operators of the Stringfellow site were to
blame because they allegedly failed to follow design specifications
in a key area of the dump site.
   The alleged error allowed toxic materials to overflow barriers
and spread into groundwater supplies, she said.
   Stringfellow attorney Christopher Bisgaard said his client
initially balked at the idea of putting the toxic dump on his
property but relented after state officials allegedly promised to
help build and operate the dump.
   Bisgaard said state geologists erroneously determined in 1955
that the quarry was located above an impermeable granite bedrock
suitable for safe dumping.
   Barry P. Goode, attorney for Rohr Industries, one of the
companies that dumped chemicals at the Stringfellow site, said the
jury decision shifted blame from companies that merely accepted
state assurances the site was safe.
   ``We were found liable without having done anything wrong,''
Goode said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
