<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--PierogiPolka     06-03 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Pierogi Polka,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polka Entrepreneur Appeals To Pierogi Lovers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fitness entrepreneur Andy LoRusso says he
wrote ``The Pierogi Diet: 101 Fun Ways to Use and Enjoy Pierogis''
to help flatten the tummies of dance lovers as well as make them
laugh.
   ``A lot of times when I dance at polka festivals, I see people
dancing polka and drinking beer, and the one food they buy is
dozens of pierogis,'' LoRusso, who sells ``PolkAerobics''
videotapes, said Friday. ``I want to reach these people.''
   The book, which sells for $2.95, details ways to cut calories
and enjoy pierogis, which are flour shells usually stuffed with
potatoes, cheese or onions.
   It suggests topping pierogis with low-fat yogurt instead of sour
cream and boiling the pasta pockets rather than frying them. It
also suggests using the treats for less orthodox purposes.
   ``They can take the pierogi and stuff it in their clothes for
shoulder pads or make a change purse out of one,'' LaRusso said.
   When promoting his book, LoRusso plays a kazoo and sings his
latest song, ``The Pittsburgh Pierogi Polka.''
</TEXT>
