<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DroughtAssistance     06-03 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Assistance,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Allows Haying, Grazing on Conservation Set-Aside Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is opening up
millions of acres of erosion-prone land for hay cutting and
livestock grazing to help farmers in drought-stricken areas.
   USDA announced the assistance on Friday, saying producers in
more than 500 counties in 16 states currently could be eligible.
   ``Livestock producers have exhausted stocks of hay that were
carried into winter, and they are now faced with another dry
spring,'' Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said. ``So they're
out of hay and short of grass.''
   The land being made available is part of a conservation reserve
program that pays people to take their most erosion-prone land out
of production for at least 10 years and improve it by planting
grasses and trees.
   The haying assistance would be authorized county by county in
states where a livestock emergency has been declared, currently 16
states, mostly in the Midwest and Great Plains, according to USDA.
   Tighter restrictions would be placed on livestock grazing on the
so-called CRP acres. It would be allowed only after a visual
inspection of the land by the Soil Conservation Service to ensure
it would not suffer any damage.
   The 16 states are: Kansas, Missouri, Iowa, Nebraska, Oklahoma,
Texas, California, Colorado, Florida, Illinois, Minnesota, New
Mexico, New York, North Dakota, South Dakota and Wisconsin.
   County offices of the Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service must seek authority for the haying and grazing
privileges. Kelly Shipp, Yeutter's press secretary, said about 570
counties in the 16 states were eligible currently to apply for the
CRP-related assistance because they had received livestock
emergency declarations. Additional counties and states could become
eligible later.
   As of last year, 28 million acres nationwide _ 19 million of
those in the 16 states _ had been enrolled in the conservation
reserve program, which was established by the 1985 farm law as a
way to reduce erosion and trim overproduction on marginal land. The
government paid $1.4 billion in yearly rental payments to producers
participating in the program.
   Friday's announcement is the latest federal aid made available
to farmers facing crop and livestock losses from lingering drought
conditions. It followed Yeutter's visit to Iowa earlier this week
and earlier visits to Nebraska and Kansas.
   USDA last month authorized livestock grazing and hay cutting on
land taken out of production under this year's commodity programs,
but put off a decision on conservation reserve acreage. In
addition, livestock and poultry producers have been allowed to buy
surplus government-owned grain at discount prices.
   These restrictions will apply to the CRP assistance:
   _Rental payments to producers next year will be cut 50 percent
for those who cut hay or graze livestock. Nationwide, annual
payments averaged $48 an acre last year.
   _No CRP land with grasses planted after July 1, 1987, will be
eligible.
   _Only one hay cutting will be allowed, and none permitted after
July 15. At least three inches of stubble must be left, and a
one-fourth of each field must be left untouched to provide cover
for wildlife.
   _Local ASCS operations will determine how long grazing will be
permitted on CRP land as well as the number of livestock. No
grazing will be allowed after Aug. 1.
</TEXT>
