<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls-CapitalRequirements     06-03 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Capital Requirements,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Capital Requirements to Rise, But Rules Likely to Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most savings and loan associations will have
to increase the amount of capital they keep in reserve, the
government says.
   The increase is required by current regulations that tie the
capital standards to the industry's annual profitability.
   As a result, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Friday that
minimum requirements for most savings and loans will rise from the
current 3.44 percent of liabilities to 3.75 percent at the start of
next year.
   The regulations would gradually increase capital requirements to
6 percent.
   The rules, however, are likely to be superseded by legislation
under consideration in Congress that would overhaul S&amp;L regulations
and require thrift operators to put more of their own money at risk
to stay in business.
   The tougher capital requirements proposed by President Bush as
part of his S&amp;L bailout package have been the subject of intense
debate on Capitol Hill, with differences between House and Senate
proposals likely to be ironed out by a joint conference committee.
   Under the changes announced Friday by the bank board, S&amp;Ls in
the standard group _ which includes healthy thrifts and covers
about 80 percent of the industry _ would see their capital
requirements rise to 3.60 percent on July 1 and to 3.75 percent
next January.
   Capital requirements vary case by case for S&amp;Ls in the lower
group _ made up of thrifts experiencing financial difficulty or
under federal supervision _ but their required capital would rise
by 0.19 percent on July 1 and another 0.18 percent next January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
