<DATELINE>WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Estrich, former Dukakis
presidential campaign manager, told graduates at the 111th
Wellesley College commencement to take precautions against crime
but not to be ruled by fear.
   She said Friday that the recent beating and rape in Central Park
of a Wellesley graduate brought memories of a tragedy that occurred
to her in 1974, two days before she graduated from Wellesley.
   ``On my way home from a rehearsal right here, in the parking lot
of my new Boston apartment, I was raped,'' she said.
   ``I cannot tell you why black teen-agers in New York would abuse
and beat a jogger, or why white teen-agers in New Jersey would
sexually abuse a mentally impaired girl they had gone to school
with all their lives,'' Estrich told the 511 graduates of the
all-women college.
   ``And you do not need me to remind you about locking doors, and
traveling in twos and, not taking unnecessary risks. I can only
tell you that after you have done all that, fear can harm you more
than crime.''
