<FIRST>r w PM-Fauntroy     06-03 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fauntroy,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Delegate to Congress Says He's Violated No Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia's non-voting
congressional delegate, whose office personnel practices are under
preliminary investigation by the Justice Department, says he has
done nothing to violate the law or the rules of Congress.
   In a statement Friday to reporters, Walter Fauntroy complained
about Justice Department leaks concerning the probe and said he is
``cooperating fully'' with authorities.
   He also said The Associated Press has ``consistently'' filed
misleading stories over the past six months.
   In declaring his innocence, Fauntroy also said the Justice
Department has ``subpoenaed personnel records that are not in my
possession nor mine to give.''
   Fauntroy, a non-voting Democratic delegate to the House, said
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh ``simply must get control of his
agency.'' He urged Thornburgh to appoint an independent counsel to
look into the news leaks that have provided the AP with material
for some of its stories.
   The AP reported last November that Thomas Savage, the son of
Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., was on Fauntroy's payroll from Sept. 8,
1987, to June 13, 1988, and that for a portion of that time he also
was campaigning for election to the Illinois Legislature. The AP
also reported that in his election petition, Savage said he resided
in Chicago.
   In his statement, Fauntroy said AP had failed to report that
Savage was placed on an unpaid leave of absence for the 10 weeks
``that he was in Chicago campaigning for a state office.''
   AP's original story on Nov. 29, 1988, reported that House
records showed Savage had been on an unpaid leave of absence for
six weeks during that period. House records that could resolve the
discrepancy were unavailable late Friday.
</TEXT>
