<DOCNO> AP890603-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IowaInvestigation     06-03 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Investigation,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Crewman's Friend Recalls Talk of Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sailor who survived the USS Iowa explosion
says he heard his friend and crewmate talk of suicide but never of
blowing up a ship.
   NBC News reported earlier Friday that investigators of the Iowa
explosion are focusing on Clayton Hartwig, who was one of the 47
sailors to die in the blast April 19.
   NBC said Hartwig was often despondent and aloof, and that he
reportedly told a witness, ``If you've got to go, go in a blast.
You go quick. You go painless.''
   But Hartwig's friend, Gunner's Mate 3rd Class Kendall Truitt,
said on ABC's ``Nightline'' that he didn't take Hartwig's talk of
suicide seriously.
   ``The way he described, you know, killing himself would have
been just simply (to) walk off the ship,'' Truitt said. ``He never
talked about an explosion.''
   Truitt said he remembered that Hartwig ``was a little down, but
it was over a year and a half ago. He had at one point (talked
about suicide) but it wasn't very serious. ... I think we all talk
about suicide at least once in our life, and at the time the
divisions were razzing him about how close friends we were.''
   NBC said Hartwig, 25, was the last man to touch the gunpowder
that exploded in the ship's second turret on April 19.
   NBC reported a witness told investigators that Hartwig showed
off a $15 timer available in hobby stores and said that if it were
rigged to a battery it could set off the ship's gunpowder and start
a chain of explosions.
   But Truitt's attorney, Ellis Rubin, said on ``Nightline'' that
he believed the explosion may have been caused by an inexperienced
crew working with gunpowder that he contended was unstable because
it was stored improperly.
   Last week, Navy investigators said the gunpowder had been stored
at unusually high temperatures at one point. But they also said
that would not have affected its stability.
   Rubin also said he had talked to an Iowa crewman who remembered
hearing someone say shortly before the blast, ``Tell them we're not
ready yet.''
   Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Chris Baumann said he could not comment
on the network report, and expressed regret that leaks about the
investigation were distressing relatives and ship's crew.
   Hartwig could have inserted a homemade detonator between bags of
gunpowder in the breech of the turret's center 16-inch gun, NBC
said. Navy explosive experts have successfully tested a similar
timing device in a simulation, the network added.
   CBS also reported that a witness told investigators that Hartwig
had shown him a timing device and said words to the effect that he
could blow the ship up. The network said no remnants of a timer
were found, but firefighting may have washed them away.
   Investigators reportedly said such a device could have given off
smoke or made a noise that could have served as a warning to other
sailors. It had been known earlier that the last words of sailor
Richard Lawrence, spoken into a internal ship telephone, were,
``We've got a problem in here.''
   A different voice was heard saying something that sounded like
``smoke smoke smoke, help help,'' NBC said.
   Many sailors' bodies were found in defensive positions, hunched
over with their arms covering their heads, the network said.
   In addition, NBC said investigators found that Hartwig had
written letters that spoke of his death and the destruction of the
second turret. The network quoted sources as saying they believed
Hartwig lived in a fantasy world and told relatives of an upcoming
transfer to London that the Navy said he had not been given.
   NBC said Truitt was heard by two other sailors as saying
immediately after the blast, ``I can't believe he actually did it.''
   Truitt said on ``Nightline'' that he did not recall making such
a statement and added, ``He (Hartwig) never talked about blowing up
a ship or anything.''
   Truitt has asked the Navy for an apology for linking his name to
the criminal investigation of the explosion. Rubin said Friday at a
news conference, ``If the Navy wants to reveal it they will, and
they're going to; he's going to be cleared.''
   Responding to Rubin's comments, Baumann said Friday night, ``How
can we clear him? We haven't accused him of anything.''
   He read from a Navy statement that said: ``The Navy recognizes
with regret the additional anguish press reports from some
unidentified sources have placed on the families of deceased Iowa
shipmates as well as the crew itself.
   ``We wish to assure these families the Navy remains committed to
a thorough and complete investigation and hopes that a responsible
public understands the need for discretion until all the factors
can be amassed and evaluated.''
   Baumann said Rubin's comments were ``the gist of why we're
putting this out.''
</TEXT>
