<FIRST>r w PM-HondurasAid     06-03 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras Aid,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Official Backs Away From Testimony on Honduras Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A State Department official is backtracking
from his denial that a plan was carried out to link aid to Honduras
with help to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, and a House subcommittee
chairman says he will ask more questions about the plan.
   Michael G. Kozak, assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, testified on April 25 that the ``plan was
disapproved, at the objection of the State Department, on the
grounds that conditionality _ linkage between U.S. assistance and
any (Honduran) assistance to the (Contra) resistance _ was contrary
to U.S. policy.''
   ``The whole proposed linkage that was included in (the) plan was
disapproved, was not made, there was no `discreet emissary,'''
Kozak told the House Appropriations subcommittee on foreign
operations chaired by Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.
   But in a letter to Obey this week, Kozak said, ``I certainly did
not intend to imply by these statements, however, that decisions to
provide assistance to Honduras on an expedited basis were not
thereafter made or carried out.''
   Kozak had testified that an admission of facts agreed to by both
sides and used in former National Security Council aide Oliver
North's trial was misleading. Among other trial documents was a
Feb. 1985 memo initialed by President Reagan and approving a plan
to link more than $110 million in extra aid to Honduras' support
for the Contra rebels.
   Then-Vice President Bush traveled to Honduras and met with
President Roberto Suazo Cordova, but Bush has said he did not
discuss any possible quid pro quo with Suazo.
   After examining the secret documents used to draw up the
admission of facts, Obey wrote Kozak that his testimony did not
seem to jibe with the documents.
   Obey said Friday that Kozak wrote back to say, ``Because I am
responding from the perspective of the department and my own
personal knowledge, I cannot speak to documents from other agencies
or the thoughts and actions of persons other than myself.''
   A separate letter to Obey from Assistant Secretary Janet Mullins
said, ``Information about non-departmental personnel and activities
should be sought from other, appropriate sources'' which she did
not specify.
   Obey said Kozak's letter to him ``seemed to indicate that his
original testimony left the wrong impression.''
   ``His letter, without specifically reversing that, simply said,
`I'm sorry if we left the impression that the plan was not carried
out,''' Obey said.
   Obey said he believed ``there's absolutely no question that it
was carried out. The documents laid out the plan ... the additional
assistance we know did arrive.''
   Kozak's letter will lead to more questions that will be
addressed both to the State Department and the White House,
including questions about aid to other Central American countries,
Obey said.
   Last month, Obey threatened to hold up $700 million in aid for
Latin America unless administration officials concede they misled
lawmakers about U.S. efforts to win third-country help for the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   Kozak did not return a message left at his home phone Friday
night.
</TEXT>
