<HEAD>US Won't Let PLO Reopen Washington Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has turned down a request
to let the Palestine Liberation Organization reopen the Washington
office the Reagan administration shut down in 1987.
   The Washington representative of the Arab League, Ambassador
Clovis Maksoud, told reporters earlier Friday that he had asked the
State Department to permit the PLO to reopen the office.
   Maksoud said it was ``mind-boggling'' for the United States to
maintain a dialogue with the PLO, begun last December, while
refusing the organization permission to reopen its office here.
   The State Department, responding to press inquiries about
Maksoud's statement, said Congress in 1987 prohibited the
establishment of any PLO office in the United States.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Byrd Urges Open Cambodian Policy</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., is urging the
administration to seek an open U.S. policy in Cambodia rather than
trying to secretly arm non-communist guerrillas there.
   ``There is much at stake here and it seems inadvisable to engage
in secret deals, secret policy, secret aid, and repeat the mistakes
of the very recent past,'' Byrd told the Senate Friday.
   ``If we are to re-engage in Southeast Asia let us do so,'' said
Byrd, the former majority leader who chairs the Appropriations
Committee. ``But let us do so only after thorough, open debate,
with discussions of options and the careful formulation of a new
U.S. policy in concert with other nations that wish to bring
long-term peace and stability to Cambodia.''
   Vietnam announced last April 1 that it will end its 10-year
occupation of Cambodia and withdraw all of its military forces by
next Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Harris Corp. Pleads No Contest</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida company has agreed to pay $200,000
in fines and $300,000 to settle civil claims by the government
arising from an investigation of fraud involving weapons sales to
the Philippines.
   Harris Corp., which is based in Melbourne, Fla., pleaded no
contest Friday to a criminal charge it aided and abetted the filing
of a false statement by a Filipino businessman convicted of
defrauding the Defense Department.
   The company entered the no-contest plea in U.S. District Court
in nearby Alexandria, Va. The action was announced by the Justice
Department in Washington.
   Harris admitted that its Farinon Division agreed to falsely
inflate to $3.38 million the value of a $2.4 million subcontract it
obtained from businessman Raymond F. Moreno to sell electronic
equipment to the Philippines military under the program, the
Justice Department said.
   Harris-Farinon agreed to kick back $1.03 million of the $3.38
million to a Hong Kong shell corporation operated by Moreno in the
guise of a marketing fee, the Justice Department said.
</TEXT>
