<FIRST>r a PM-Alar Bjt   06-03 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alar, Bjt,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alar Sales in United States Halted by Manufacturer; Move Draws Praise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voluntary decision by Alar's
manufacturer to take the chemical off the U.S. market drew praise
from the nation's apple belt as the best way to win back consumers.
   Uniroyal Chemical Co. continued to defend the chemical as safe,
but said Friday that continued use on apples raised public doubts
about the safety of America's food supply. The chemical has been
labeled a possible carcinogen, although tests are continuing.
   ``We should be hopeful and expect this will be the beginning of
restoring consumer confidence,'' said John McAlister, a spokesman
for Selah-based Tree Top Inc., the nation's largest apple juice
maker.
   But other industry figures said the action is unlikely to help
the current crop, which has turned into a financial disaster.
   Prices have fallen 40 percent, to below the cost of production,
and Washington state has 3.3 million more boxes of apples in
storage than at this time last year. That includes an unknown
quantity of Alar-treated apples that may have to be dumped.
   ``It won't make any difference for this year, but it certainly
should help us as far as sales for next year's crop,'' said Bill
DeWitt of the Wenatchee Valley Traffic Association, which charts
apple sales.
   Washington state produces about half the nation's apples and has
about 12 million of the 42-pound boxes in storage.
   Apple growers and processors nationwide had pleaded with
Uniroyal to withdraw Alar. Public fears had cost each group an
estimated $100 million in sales so far this year, industry groups
estimate.
   The voluntary withdrawal by Uniroyal, which is based in
Middlebury, Conn., means consumers will be guaranteed that this
fall's apple crop will be Alar-free, said Tom Hale of the
Washington State Apple Commission.
   Sales of daminozide, which is sold under the name Alar, would
continue to about 70 foreign markets, including some that export
apples and apple products to this country, Uniroyal said.
   Supplies of the chemical held by U.S. customers may be returned
for refunds, the company said.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said late Friday it has
reached agreement with Uniroyal on a plan to monitor the removal of
Alar from the U.S. market, although it is still legal to use. The
agency also said it will notify foreign governments about agency
concerns about Alar.
   The EPA has said it plans to ban use of daminozide in food
products because tests in laboratory animals have linked a
byproduct of Alar with cancer after the chemical is heated. Final
action on the proposed regulation is not expected until late 1990.
   Uniroyal has disputed the findings and company Vice President
James Wylie said Friday: ``We want to emphasize that we have not
changed our opinion about the safety of daminozide.''
   The EPA estimates that from 5 percent to 15 percent of the U.S.
apple crop is treated with Alar, a growth regulator that improves
the apple's appearance and gives it a longer shelf life.
   The Alar issue was ignited by the private Natural Resources
Defense Council's report that concluded that eating Alar-treated
apples increased cancer risk, especially in children.
   The findings have been disputed by the apple industry and
several federal agencies, including EPA, declared apples safe to
eat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
