<FIRST>r a PM-NewBridge Bjt   06-03 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Bridge, Bjt,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Expensive Freeway Segment Ever Built Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With much fanfare, authorities Sunday are opening
a seven-mile stretch of Interstate 90 that has the dubious
distinction of being the most expensive segment of freeway ever
built.
   It is part of a $1.46 billion highway project for the
mushrooming Seattle metropolis to build roads that probably will be
badly congested by the time they are completed in 1994.
   For the time being, the new link between Seattle and Bellevue
across Lake Washington brings welcome relief from the twice-daily
creep across the lake's two existing four-lane spans that become
jammed by fender-benders.
   Commuters also say goodbye to an infamous I-90 lane that
switched direction depending on the commute. With no barrier to
separate traffic, motorists tagged it the ``death lane.''
   The completed segment includes a floating bridge, a
triple-decker tunnel with one level for bicycles and pedestrians,
and a concrete-slab roof over sections of the highway that will be
landscaped as parks.
   The freeway, proposed in 1957, drew the wrath of residents, who
wanted to protect neighborhoods, and of environmentalists.
   In 1971, planners agreed to scale back the project and build
tunnels on the Seattle side of the lake, but an environmental
impact statement wasn't approved until 1979.
   By then, federal money had dried up, and it wasn't until
Congress raised the gas tax in 1982 that funds became available.
Construction began in earnest the next year.
   So far, $860 million has been spent. The balance of the money
will go to reopening and linking up one of the old bridges, located
to the south of the new structure, as well as other additions.
   At about $200 million a mile, the freeway has set a record for
costliness, but one that will soon fall to a project at I-90's
other terminus _ Boston, according to Seattle project manager Brian
Henkel.
   That $4.4 billion project will rebuild Interstate 93 through
downtown Boston and construct a third harbor tunnel to link I-90
with Logan International Airport.
   Despite ``a major crisis every second day,'' Henkel said, he is
on time and $16 million under budget. The project includes the
world's largest soft-ground tunnel _ 1,500 feet long and 63 feet in
diameter _ Henkel said.
   Henkel said he still sees vestiges of the rancor that surrounded
the project.
   ``But now, it's almost opposite to the earlier emotion of `make
the freeway as difficult as possible to get on and maybe they won't
build it,''' he said. ``Now they say, `I live in Seattle and work
on the Eastside and there's no way I can get on I-90 conveniently.''
   King County east of Lake Washington has grown in the past two
decades from small towns and farms to a suburban area of 360,000
people. Another 275,000 are expected by 2020, said Mike Smith,
senior transportation planner for the Puget Sound Council of
Governments.
   The county, which includes Seattle, has a population of about
1.4 million. Studies have shown the population of King and
surrounding counties will grow by about 500,000 in the next decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
