<FIRST>r a PM-YearbooksRecalled     06-03 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yearbooks Recalled,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic High School Recalls Yearbooks Because Of Offensive Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The student yearbook at a Catholic high school
was recalled after officials discovered the books contained sexual
innuendo and insults directed at faculty members.
   Seniors at St. Ignatius High School were told unless they
returned their yearbooks, they could not go to graduation
ceremonies Sunday, while underclassmen were told they could not
advance to the next grade if they failed to return the books, the
Rev. Robert Welsh, school president, said Friday.
   Thirty-eight of the 800 books printed remained unaccounted for
Friday night, Welsh said.
   ``There were unacceptable captions and unacceptable stories,''
Welsh said. ``There were sexual references and there was also bad
taste and rather insulting remarks to the faculty.''
   Welsh said six of eight seniors who worked on the yearbooks
apologized to faculty and staff Friday afternoon. Some parents
accompanied the students, he said.
   ``I would say the faculty accepted the apology. As a Catholic
school we feel we are called to forgive those who ask for
forgiveness,'' Welsh said.
   He said no disciplinary action would be taken against the six
students.
   The Plain Dealer reported today the captions were apparently
written after the yearbook's adviser had been injured in a car
accident.
   The yearbook staffers later showed the adviser phony page
proofs, which the teacher approved, then the students sent the real
pages to the publisher, the newspaper said.
   There are 277 seniors among the 1,200 male students at St.
Ignatius.
</TEXT>
