<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Not-So-HotFudge     06-03 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Not-So-Hot Fudge,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venerable Ice Cream Parlor, Inventor of Hot Fudge Sundae, Tries Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bailey's, the venerable chain of ice cream parlors
where the hot fudge sundae was invented, is trying to make a
comeback under new ownership after a disastrous experiment in
yuppie marketing.
   Last year, five of its seven stores closed, including the
landmark location in Cambridge's Harvard Square, where the mahogany
paneling and marble table tops were ripped out for a pizzeria.
   The 116-year-old chain's former owner, Joey Crugnale, admits he
goofed in trying to remake Bailey's as an upscale spot for people
in their 20s and 30s.
   ``It was a mistake from the beginning,'' he said. ``But I'm not
ashamed of it. I learned a lot from it.''
   Michael Mazzaferro, one of three brothers who bought the
business in November for an undisclosed price, said he hopes to
reopen stores in Boston and Cambridge within the next few years.
   ``I think the company lost its focus and it became more of a
luncheon stop as opposed to an old-fashioned candy store and ice
cream parlor,'' he said. ``We want to restore it to its roots.''
   The Mazzaferro family, which has been making candy in
Massachusetts since the 1950s, already is turning out Bailey's
fudge at the rate of 20,000 pounds a year.
   That would gladden the heart of Sarah Dow, the bookkeeper to
founder John Bailey. When he retired in 1900, she became the shop's
owner and took a gamble that made dessert history.
   ``She put 6 ounces of ice cream in a 5-ounce dish and poured one
and a half ounces of hot fudge on top of it, and it dripped down
onto the silver dish,'' Frank Wyman Jr., a former Bailey's owner,
said with reverence. ``Beautiful concept. Beautiful product.''
   Later, Bailey's supplied mail-order chocolates to Theodore
Roosevelt, Calvin Coolidge and John F. Kennedy. Joseph Kennedy Sr.,
the late president's father, was among the many Boston brahmins who
kept his candy preferences on record at the flagship store on
Temple Place, at the edge of the Boston Common.
   Shortly after Crugnale bought the chain in January 1987 for a
reported $1.5 million, he announced plans to open more than 100
stores throughout New England in seven or eight years.
   But one of his first moves was to decide there was ``just no
future'' in the old-fashioned menu of sandwiches like chopped ham
and pickles, peanut butter and bacon, and datenut bread and cream
cheese.
   Although ``little old ladies'' who had been faithful customers
for decades implored him to reconsider, Crugnale said, he held firm.
   The entrepreneur, 37, had made a fortune with a yuppie, trendy,
gourmet ice cream chain called Steve's and a yuppie, trendy,
gourmet pizza chain called Bertucci's.
   So he ignored the old ladies and pulled the same trick with
Bailey's.
   It didn't work.
   When Crugnale sold the chain to the Mazzaferros last fall, it
was down to two stores, both in the suburbs.
   Crugnale, who had built Steve's Ice Cream from one store to a
national chain of 26 before selling out in 1983, says he was
probably overconfident when he took over Bailey's.
   ``I thought I was superman _ I did Steve's, I could do
anything,'' he said.
   Though humbled by his failure with Bailey's, Crugnale has made a
roaring success of Bertucci's, now a chain of 12 pizzerias in
Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
   ``Bailey's was a business we shouldn't have been in,'' he said.
``Bertucci's is one I'm much more comfortable with.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
