<FIRST>r a PM-RefugeeStandoff     06-03 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugee Standoff,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Officials Question Haitian Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haitian refugees threatened to throw babies
overboard during an eight-hour standoff at sea before agreeing to
board Coast Guard cutters, officials said.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service agents Friday were
interviewing 109 Haitians after flying to the scene about 100 miles
south of Miami, said Lt. Jeff Karonis, a Coast Guard spokesman.
   Karonis said the refugees brandished knives and machetes when
their 50-foot wooden sailboat was intercepted Thursday by the Coast
Guard.
   The refugees refused to let the Coast Guard board their boat,
Karonis said, and the group's leader threatened to throw five
babies overboard.
   The Coast Guard cutters Shearwater and Matagorda were sent out
to help a third cutter, the Metompkin, which made the interception.
   During the standoff, the INS agents and an interpreter were
airlifted to the scene.
   Late Thursday, after hours of negotiations, INS and Coast Guard
officials managed ``to convince the Haitians to go peacefully'' to
the cutters, Karonis said.
   No one was injured, and a small Coast Guard launch crew rescued
a woman who jumped overboard during the standoff.
   Two of the Haitians were airlifted from the scene to Miami's
Jackson Memorial Hospital. One was suffering from hypothermia,
Karonis said, and the other appeared to have suffered a seizure.
   The hospital on Friday refused to release details of their
condition.
</TEXT>
