<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0556EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern     06-03 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wages Down, Vacations Out at Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wages are down, work hours are up and vacations are
out at Eastern Airlines, which announced an austerity program
designed to help the strike-crippled company rebuild from
bankruptcy.
   Eastern said Friday it will eliminate vacations for the rest of
the year, cut management pay by 20 percent and require non-union
employees to work 50 hours a week for 40 hours of pay.
   Meanwhile, a judge in New York gave an investor group friendly
with striking employees until Monday afternoon to refine a buyout
proposal. The group is led by Chicago commodities trader Joseph
Ritchie.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland's decree surprised
observers who thought he would dismiss the Ritchie proposal as
financially inadequate and vague.
   But David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed examiner for Eastern,
told Lifland he was impressed by a new version of the plan under
which the unions would risk $175 million to $200 million of their
wages over six months.
   Eastern sought protection from creditors under bankruptcy laws
five days after pilots and flight attendants joined striking
Machinists on March 4, reducing the airline's flights by more than
90 percent.
   The company plans to expand service and recall some 1,700
non-union employees by July 2.
   ``It's a unique situation. We're going to be the fastest-growing
airline in history during the time we're going to be in
bankruptcy,'' said Thomas J. Matthews, senior vice president for
human resources.
   Under the austerity program, full-time agents and clerical
workers will be scheduled to work 50 hours a week without a pay
increase through Dec. 1. Management also will work at least 50
hours a week.
   No vacations will be allowed through year's end, and no vacation
credit will be accrued from March to December this year.
   Salaries for about 25 corporate officers, including Eastern
President Phil Bakes, will be reduced 20 percent through the end of
the year and 10 percent for the first six months of 1990.
   The company's proposals for pilots and flight attendants will be
discussed when negotiations with the unions representing those
groups resume next week, Matthews said.
   Union officials said the austerity program proves the company's
reorganization plan is failing.
   ``They're not getting the revenue coming in to sustain the
people on the payroll,'' said Wally Haber, a spokesman for the
Machinists.
   Eastern is operating with 5,000 workers, most of them management
employees. The company had 30,000 workers before the strike and
plans to have 17,000 when its reorganization is completed by year's
end.
   The number of management jobs will be reduced from 2,900 before
the strike to 1,900, and about 1,000 management employees will be
reassigned to non-management jobs, Matthews said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
