<DOCNO> AP890603-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Libya     06-03 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Libya,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hug May Lead to Warmer Ties Between Libya, Egypt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the Arab world's bitterest rivalries
seems headed toward resolution following a bearhug in Morocco.
   The hugger was Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, who a few days
earlier had threatened to boycott the Arab League summit meeting at
Casablanca if Egypt's Hosni Mubarak showed up. Mubarak was the one
hugged.
   That was May 23.
   Since then, invective has halted from both sides of the
Egyptian-Libyan border, now open for the first time in more than a
decade.
   Unannounced, Egypt canceled military exercises scheduled this
week in the desert between Cairo and Libya and is expected to
reduce forces concentrated there since the early 1970s.
   Further, a Libyan aircraft has landed at Cairo International
Airport for the first time in years, with a promise of regular
commercial service starting Monday.
   And Col. Gadhafi's cousin and intelligence chief, Ahmed Gaddaf
Dam, spent two days in Cairo, including a meeting Wednesday night
with the Egyptian president.
   If the drama plays out, Libya, the United States's most strident
Arab enemy, soon could restore relations with Egypt, one of
Washington's best friends in the region.
   On Wednesday, Mubarak told journalists that relations between
the two countries ``are on the threshold of a new era based on a
right foundation of frankness.''
   Several newspapers reported Gadhafi would visit Egypt, some
saying he would drive to Alexandria, 300 miles east of the border.
   ``It would be just like him,'' said a Foreign Ministry source on
condition of anonymity. ``But we shouldn't jump to conclusions. We
should take it easy and not forget that Gadhafi can just as
suddenly change his mind.''
   Makram Mohamed Ahmed, a magazine editor and Mubarak confidant,
wrote that it is realistic to expect the reopening of borders and
airports but ``difficult, for varying reasons, to talk about plans
for the far future.''
   The first major strains in relations occurred in 1972, when
Gadhafi proposed a merger of the two north African neighbors that
was rejected by Mubarak's predecessor, Anwar Sadat. The break
occurred in 1977 with a brief border war after Sadat accused
Gadhafi of sponsoring terror bombings in Egypt.
   Mubarak's government has charged Gadhafi with several attempts
to assassinate Libyan dissidents in Egypt, several of whom
coordinate anti-Gadhafi campaigns from their Egyptian exile. It
also suspected but was unable to prove that Libya laid mines in the
Red Sea in 1984.
   Libya still has no embassy or diplomatic interests section in
Cairo, and Libyan dissidents, while not knowing what to expect,
still receive police protection.
   Gadhafi has asked Mubarak to send home the exiles, many of them
thriving businessmen.
   Egypt has refused.
   Libyan exiles had transmitted messages of defiance to their
countrymen back home on Radio Cairo's Voice of the Arabs. A source
at the official radio service said, however, that the station
stopped its anti-Gadhafi rhetoric shortly before the Casablanca
summit.
   In Libya, the official news agency JANA also has changed its
tone.
   On Thursday, it distributed a report of a telegram to Gadhafi
from a prominent Sudanese politician congratulating ``yourself and
the Arab nation for normalizing brotherly relations'' with Egypt.
   And since the summit meeting, JANA has called the Egyptian
president Mubarak instead of its usual term, ``Al-Barek'' _ an
insulting term describing a kneeling camel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
