<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Soviet     06-03 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Soviet,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Britons Expelled for Alleged Espionage Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven of 11 Britons expelled by the Soviet Union
for alleged espionage have returned to Britain, and one of them, TV
journalist Ian Glover-James, called the allegations
``incomprehensible.''
   The Soviets last month ordered out eight British diplomats and
three journalists in response to Britain's expulsion of 11 Soviets
also accused of espionage. The seven arrived home Friday.
   Glover-James, who had been based in Moscow for two years with
Independent Television News, told reporters at Heathrow Airport,
``I'm a correspondent, a news reporter, nothing else. I've never
done anything else in the entire two years I've been there.''
   ``To me, they (the allegations) are incomprehensible,'' he said.
``It's impossible to understand them, I don't recognize them and
they certainly don't apply to me.''
   Glover-James said he would like to visit Moscow again, but his
chances of being allowed back in ``are not very hopeful,'' he said.
``That's very disappointing.''
   Capt. Christopher Meyer, the British Embassy's expelled naval
attache, said he was saddened to leave the country.
   Asked about the allegations, Meyer replied, ``I'm not a spy.''
</TEXT>
