<FIRST>r a PM-CottonClub     06-03 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cotton Club,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surprise Testimony Halts `Cotton Club' Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note offensive language in 3rd and 18th grafs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution's star witness in ``The
Cotton Club'' murder case testified that two bodyguards bragged
about killing producer Roy Radin.
   The surprise testimony Friday prompted the judge to halt a
preliminary hearing under way to determine if enough evidence
exists for trial.
   William Rider said two defendants bragged to him about the Radin
murder and one of them said ``he enjoyed shooting the big fat Jew.''
   Angry defense lawyers interrupted Rider's testimony, objecting
that they had not been told about at least 10 statements he had
made in less than an hour on the stand Friday.
   The lawyers accused prosecutors of hiding incriminating
information, which is prohibited under California laws. Deputy
District Attorney David Conn insisted he had disclosed ``the gist
of the statements,'' but Municipal Court Judge Patti Jo McKay said
that was insufficient.
   She stopped the hearing and ordered prosecution investigators to
appear in court Monday to disclose everything they know about
Rider's planned testimony. If more material is uncovered, she said
she would grant the defense a continuance.
   Rider, Hustler magazine Publisher Larry Flynt's brother-in-law
and former chief of security, implicated two of Flynt's former
bodyguards, William Molony Mentzer and Alex Lamota Marti, who are
charged in the May 1983 Radin murder.
   Rider's claim that the two confessed to him triggered charges in
the six-year-old murder in October. He also implicated reputed drug
dealer Karen DeLayne Greenberger and former Paramount Pictures
chief Robert Evans, who has refused to testify citing fears he
might incriminate himself. Evans is not charged.
   Mrs. Greenberger, who is charged in the murder, introduced Radin
and Evans in a deal to finance the movie, ``The Cotton Club.''
   Rider's new statements from the witness stand were more detailed
than those he had given before. He said Marti and Mentzer boasted
to him in May or June 1983 about the Radin murder.
   ``It was sometime before the body was found and after the
killing,'' he said, recalling a conversation with Mentzer at
Flynt's house.
   ``What did Mr. Mentzer say?'' asked Conn.
   ``Only that he had just done a hit and dumped the body up by
where we went target practicing,'' said Rider.
   Radin disappeared on May 13, 1983. His body was found a month
later in a dry riverbed about 65 miles north of Los Angeles. He had
been shot repeatedly in the head.
   In June, Rider said, Mentzer and Marti brought him a newspaper
article about the discovery of Radin's body and said it proved they
were telling the truth. He said they referred to Radin by the
nickname ``Rodan,'' and offered more details.
   ``Mr. Marti said that in reference to Mr. Mentzer getting the
courage to shoot Mr. Radin, that he had to drink a bottle of wine
before. Mr. Marti shot first and emptied his gun into Mr. Radin and
Mr. Mentzer followed suit,'' said Rider.
   ``What else did Mr. Marti say?'' asked Deputy District Attorney
David Conn.
   ``Just that he hated Jews and he enjoyed shooting the big fat
Jew,'' said Rider.
   Rider, who is being paid $3,000 a month as a protected
prosecution witness, has said he fears he will be killed because of
his testimony.
   Also charged is Robert Ulmer Lowe, who is fighting extradition
in Maryland.
</TEXT>
