<FIRST>r a PM-Presbyterians     06-03 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presbyterians,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Hear Call for Unity from National Council of Churches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the National Council of
Churches told Presbyterians at a bicentennial symposium that a
major goal is to create one Christian church that cares about the
whole world.
   ``Our highest allegiance is not to one denomination or one
nation,'' the Rev. Patricia McClurg said Friday at a symposium on
the future preceding Tuesday's start of the 201st General Assembly
of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.). ``When we are doing our work
we see ourselves as part of one church. The pledge is to one God
and savior.''
   She acknowledged that U.S. Presbyterian leaders are worried
today that they are still losing members and influence in the
United States, ``and we do need to work on it with all due
seriousness and vigor.''
   But worldwide, she added, ``the Presbyterian Church is on fire
with church growth in Korea and Africa, on fire with its spiritual
and public witness in Taiwan. Our church daily is the difference
between life and death to millions of people across this planet
Earth.''
   The church, which has seen its membership decline from 4 million
to nearly 3 million since 1970, held its first General Assembly in
Philadelphia in 1789.
   The assembly starting Tuesday will involve 622 voting delegates
and an estimated 10,000 participants and observers.
   Among the items on the agenda for the voting delegates is the
selection of a new church moderator, or head.
</TEXT>
