<FIRST>r a PM-PedwayPredicament     06-03 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pedway Predicament,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ends Don't Meet on State, City Pedway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Question: Why did the bureaucrat cross the road?
   Answer: Because the underground passage, built by the city and
state from opposite directions, didn't meet in the middle.
   ``Only in Chicago could we be building our tunnel and they be
building their tunnel ... and I guess we missed,'' Mayor Richard M.
Daley joked Friday about the pedway linking City Hall and the State
of Illinois Building across Randolph Street.
   But he got serious when he told reporters he was demanding a
full report on who was to blame for the mix-up and why the city has
agreed to pay for about $240,000 worth of corrections.
   The state's portion was a few inches too far east of the city's
(eight to be exact) and a few more inches below (nine).
   The problem started when the city hired contractors to dig its
half of the pedway and the state contracted with other people to do
their half. The result was a four-year delay in opening the tunnel.
   The opening is now set for September.
   The mix-up sounds like an episode from a comic opera, but at
least one taxpayer is not amused.
   ``The city screwed up or the state screwed up, but either way,
us taxpayers get the bill. So what's new?'' said James McGee,
standing outside City Hall and in front of a plywood wall erected
to keep pedestrians from the work site.
   ``I came down here to get my vehicle sticker and I'm glad I did.
The way the city is throwing away money,'' added McGee, a
meatcutter, ``it'll probably cost me more next year.''
   The city appropriated $240,000 to cover the cost of correcting
the mistakes, said mayoral spokeswoman Marj Halperin. A published
figure of $309,000 included money spent on non-corrective work, she
said.
   The changes include a new steel-frame skeleton to accomodate a
stairway instead of a ramp, and the addition of an elevator stop at
City Hall to give the handicapped the same access to the pedway
that was lost when the ramp had to be scrapped.
   ``To put it simply, we planned a 100-foot-long ramp from City
Hall into the pedway,'' said John C. Hill, the city's coordinating
architect. ``But we had to scrap it because hooking the segments as
they sit right now would leave a slope too steep for the state code
(regarding handicapped access).
   ``That meant abandoning a lot of what was there and redoing it.
We were both supposed to come in at 22 feet, 4 inches below ground
level and somebody didn't,'' Hill concluded.
   That somebody isn't the state, insists Capital Development Board
spokeswoman Mia Jazo.
   ``We don't want to get into any more finger-pointing,'' she
said, ``but our portion is exactly where it should be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
