<FIRST>r i PM-TorontoBoom     06-03 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toronto Boom,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>With New SkyDome, is Canada's Largest City `Choking on Success?'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dollar figures U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new $355 million SkyDome stadium is the
latest symbol of Toronto's rise to major league stature, but it has
also led to questions about traffic congestion, crime and urban
woes in Canada's largest city.
   Residents have poured civic pride into preparations for this
evening's gala for the world's first stadium with a retractable
roof. But many residents wonder how this fast-growing city can
handle more downtown crowds.
   The concerns however go much further than downtown to address
the quality of life throughout the booming metropolitan area, which
has reached a population of nearly 4 million decades sooner than
expected.
   ``We're really to some extent choking on our growth,'' said John
Bossons, an economics professor at the University of Toronto who
long has been involved in municipal issues. ``We've been too
successful in a sense.''
   He recalled a transportation study of five or six years ago that
projected a metropolitan population of 4 million by the year 2011.
Five million people in metropolitan Toronto, which had half that
many residents in 1971, now seems more appropriate for 2011.
   The 60,000-seat Skydome, at the foot of the landmark CN Tower,
will be the home of the Toronto Blue Jays of baseball's American
League and the Canadian Football League's Toronto Argonauts.
   The Skydome roof was designed to open or close in 20 minutes,
but inspectors found exposed wiring, missing sprinklers and faulty
fire prevention devices among 150 deficiencies. An operating permit
finally was granted Thursday, but critics say deficiencies remain
in the stadium, which they call another example of development run
amuck.
   Critics also predict that fans will swamp already crowded
streets and highways with the extra traffic to the complex.
   Toronto has prided itself on keeping residential neighborhoods
near downtown. Its public transit system still is considered a
model. Movie set designers have to scatter garbage on the streets
when trying to make Toronto look like an American city.
   Not short on civic cheer, the city is seeking the 1996 Summer
Olympics and a world's fair for the year 2000.
   Pat Petersen, director of the urban studies program at the
University of Toronto, said residents are troubled at their
recollections of a calmer, different Toronto 10 or 15 years ago.
   ``It isn't that it's bad; it's just becoming a city,'' she said.
   Supporters of a movement that promises to firmly regulate
development won a majority of city council seats in a municipal
election late last year.
   ``It was very, very clear in the election that people were
really concerned about what they perceive as a decline in the
quality of life,'' Bosson said.
   ``We're a city at the crossroads,'' Jack Layton, one of the most
visible council members, said in an interview. ``I think the city
has been a little too smug in thinking of itself as such a
success.''
   He said the housing problems in Toronto should be getting more
attention than stadium-building.
   A newspaper poll of 1,800 people taken for a 10-part series in
the Toronto Star last month found that 35.6 percent of city
residents were more afraid of walking alone at night than five
years ago and 48 percent more afraid of riding the subway alone at
night.
   ``We still brag that Canada's largest city doesn't have half the
problems that are sucking the life out of urban America,'' the
series wrote. ``But suddenly we aren't so sure that it can't happen
to us.''
   Housing costs have soared in the economic boom that has lasted
through most of the decade, pushing the average cost of a Toronto
home to more than $232,000 and making ``affordable housing'' a
prime city issue.
   The only other Canadian city that even comes close is Vancouver,
where the average price has risen to $176,700. The average housing
price in Montreal is $92,600 and in Edmonton, Alberta, $71,600.
</TEXT>
