<DOCNO> AP890603-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Smog     06-03 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Smog,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bush To Propose Alternative Fuels Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush plans to press 25 U.S. cities
to begin converting to alternative fuels as early as 1992 to battle
urban smog, a newspaper reported today.
   The most stringent of the four options Bush is considering would
require that 50 percent of all new cars, trucks and buses in the 25
cities be required to run on alternative fuels by 1995, the Los
Angeles Times reported.
   The least stringent option would require only buses and official
automobiles in those cities to use alternative fuels, but would
accelerate the deadline to 1992, the Times said.
   The cities were not identified in the 42-page White House
document prepared by the President's Domestic Policy Council and
obtained by the Times. But the cities would include Los Angeles,
New York, Chicago, Houston, Denver and other major urban areas, the
Times said.
   The president's alternative fuels plan represents the central
element of his effort to revive and overhaul the federal effort _
stalled under the Reagan Administration _ to combat pollution in
major cities.
   Alternative fuels, including compressed natural gas, methanol
and ethanol, burn more cleanly than gasoline and reduce the
production of ozone, the major component of smog.
   Even the stringent pollution-reduction plan outlined for the
president would leave 23 cities in violation of federal air
standards by the year 2005. Last summer, 81 cities fell short of
the federal standards.
   The cost of the various proposals was not outlined in the
document presented to Bush, but estimates range from $2.1 billion
to $4.6 billion, the Times said.
   The report says that the use of alternative fuels would
``obviate the need for other more costly automobile controls'' on
emissions. Controls such as changes in tail pipes and fuel pumps
have been strongly opposed by U.S. auto makers.
   The report also suggests that cities be given the opportunity to
``opt out'' of the alternative fuels requirement if they can find
other was to reduce smog substantially.
   The report was presented to Bush before he left last weekend for
Europe. It faces final review Monday during a meeting of the
Domestic Policy Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
