<DOCNO> AP890603-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SeabrookProtest     06-03 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook Protest,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Gather for Big Anti-Seabrook Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rally begins at noon EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists demonstrating this weekend at
the Seabrook nuclear power plant say the imminent start of atomic
testing at the reactor should help their cause.
   ``Now it's beginning to sound real. Before it was sounding kind
of nebulous,'' Wes Crocheron of the anti-nuclear Clamshell Alliance
said Friday night as the first demonstrators began trickling into
this seacoast town.
   ``People are fired up against the nuke, especially now that they
got the low-power testing license,'' Crocheron said.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission gave Seabrook a low-power
testing licence last week. The first atomic chain reaction is
expected at the reactor by the middle of next week.
   The alliance was planning a major rally today at Hampton Beach
State Park, on the crowded beach peninsula less than two miles from
Seabrook that is a focal point of the struggle over whether the $6
billion reactor ever will operate commercially. Evacuation plans
for the beaches and communities up to 10 miles away from the plant
must be approved before the plant may operate commercially.
   On Sunday, the activists plan a mass civil disobedience action
at the plant site. Clamshell spokesman Paul Gunter said at least
300 to 500 people already had undergone non-violent civil
disobedience training, and more training sessions were being held
throughout the weekend.
   On Friday, Superior Court Judge Vincent Dunn denied Seabrook
town officials' request for an injunction against Sunday's
demonstration.
   Seabrook police Chief Paul Cronin indicated Friday police may
arrest demonstrators before they reach the plant gates on Sunday.
Some of the protesters hope to scale fences around the outer plant
boundary and symbolically ``occupy'' the site.
   Protest organizers hope this weekend's demonstrations will be
the largest in more than a decade at Seabrook. There have been
about 2,500 arrests in protests that began when construction
started in 1976, including 1,414 arrests in a May 1977 protest that
helped make Seabrook a symbol of the nation's anti-nuclear movement.
</TEXT>
