<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Transplants     06-03 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplants,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organ Preservation Solution Revolutionizing Field</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clinicians are preserving transplant organs for
longer periods in an improved chemical solution that is healthier
for patients and gives doctors more leeway in scheduling surgery.
   ``This solution is clearly better than what's been available.
It's a major advance in transplantation,'' said Dr. Robert Gordon,
associate professor of surgery at the University of Pittsburgh.
   The biggest impact has been in liver transplants, where half of
all organs go to waste because of logistical and organizational
problems, said the University of Wisconsin's Dr. Folkert Belzer,
who developed the solution.
   His mixture, previously available to select transplant centers
on an experimental basis, was approved for general use last month
by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
   The solution includes hormones, amino acids and sugars. It
prevents tissue swelling and cell deterioration from the time the
organ is removed from a brain-dead victim until it is transplanted.
   Under the older preservation method, livers were chilled and
flushed with Euro-Collins solution, a mix of electrolytes and
glucose.
   With the older solution, surgical teams had to spring into
action as soon as donor organs were found and transplant candidates
had to live near the center. Transplants often began in the middle
of the night, with one operation sometimes starting as soon as
another finished.
   Organs regularly were turned down because of a lack of doctors
or surgical space.
   ``This is the first time we've ever been able to do a liver and
pancreas electively,'' Belzer said Friday at the annual meeting of
the American Society of Transplant Surgeons.
   The Wisconsin solution, called ViaSpan and marketed by Du Pont,
has allowed for greater sharing of organs. Last fall, for example,
a liver was shipped from Toronto to Paris and successfully
transplanted. Another was shipped from the United States to Brazil.
   It's also enabled doctors to trim livers for young recipients or
split them for two patients when necessary.
   Studies in the United States and Europe have found livers can be
preserved safely outside the body for as long as 36 hours with the
solution, compared to a maximum six to eight hours with other
methods, said Dr. James Southard of the University of Wisconsin.
   Pancreases have been stored for as long as 29 hours with the
solution, Southard said.
   The preservation time for kidneys remains about the same, 30 to
40 hours, regardless of which solution is used, Southard said. But
studies show recipients of kidneys preserved in the Wisconsin
mixture do not return as often to dialysis because of organ
rejection and other problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
