<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-EpiscopalConference     06-03 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Episcopal Conference,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Episcopalians Form Church Within Denomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Episcopalians reacting to
the election of the first woman bishop have created a new
association to ``transform'' their denomination.
   Nearly 2,000 people attended the founding meeting of the
Episcopal Synod of America Friday. The delegates adopted a
constitution Friday and planned to end their meeting today.
   The dissident church members said they were displeased with
loosening strictures on marriage, tolerance of homosexuality,
feminist theology, revisions of liturgical language to be
gender-inclusive and what they saw as slackening standards of
personal morality in the Episcopal Church.
   ``If we remain a church within the church, our goal isn't to be
a small cell, but to be a witness to hopefully transform our
religion,'' said Bishop David Schofield of the Episcopal Diocese of
San Joaquin in Fresno, Calif.
   But members of the new church say they do not intend to break
with the nearly 2.5 million-member Episcopal Church, which has lost
about a quarter of its members since doctrinal controversies
reached their peak in the mid-1970s. The church is one of 27
branches of the 70 million-member Anglican Communion worldwide.
   Bishop Clarence Pope of Fort Worth was elected president of the
new association. He said the Episcopal Church's laws do not prevent
the traditionalists from forming a voluntary association, and he
called for the acceptance of the new organization as a way for
traditionalists to stay within the church.
   Twenty-one other Episcopal bishops, 16 of them retired, have
endorsed the synod.
   Leaders of the Fort Worth-based Evangelical and Catholic
Mission, a traditionalist group, called the synod after the Rev.
Barbara Harris was consecrated as the first female Episcopal bishop
last year in Massachusetts.
   ``This year we will have women bishops, next year they'll delete
a book or two from the New Testament,'' said Oswald Clark, a lay
member of the General Synod Church of the Church of England. ``The
substance of the question remains the same: On what ground do you
stand?''
   The new synod passed a resolution recommending usage of the 1928
Book of Common Prayer, which is discouraged by the church,
alongside the 1979 revision.
</TEXT>
