<FIRST>r a PM-FamilySlaying     06-03 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Slaying,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accountant Charged with Murder Wept During Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church-going accountant accused of
murdering five relatives in New Jersey 18 years ago broke down in
tears several times during a visit from his minister.
   ``There seemed to be some relief about him,'' said the Rev.
Joseph M. Vought, who visited John E. List, 63, in jail Friday.
``Whether that was reflective of the fact that he didn't have to
put up the front anymore, I don't know.''
   FBI agents arrested List _ known to his wife, employer and
neighbors in the Richmond suburb of Midlothian as Robert P. Clark _
Thursday on charges of fleeing to avoid prosecution for the Nov. 9,
1971, slayings of five family members in Westfield, N.J.
   ``His wife had no idea who he was,'' said John McGinley, head of
the Newark, N.J., FBI office. ``Her reaction was disbelief and
shock.''
   A tip resulting from a May 21 broadcast of the Fox Broadcasting
Co. television show ``America's Most Wanted,'' which dramatized the
crimes, led to List's arrest.
   List did not change his appearance or his profession after the
killings, but moved to Colorado, where he met his current wife at a
Lutheran church function in 1977 and married her eight years later,
authorities said.
   ``I was shocked to hear about Bob's arrest and what he was
charged with,'' said Delores Clark, who married the man she knew as
Bob Clark in 1985.
   ``This is not the man I know,'' she told The Richmond News
Leader. ``The man I know is kind, loving, a devoted husband and a
dear friend.''
   An attorney for List, David P. Baugh, said Friday that his
client had declined a bond hearing and will remain in the Henrico
County jail. A removal and probable cause hearing was set for
Thursday in federal court.
   FBI agent Kevin N. August, who was among the three FBI agents
who arrested List, said List initially denied he was the man sought
by authorities.
   Agents took List to the Richmond Bureau of Police, where a
fingerprint expert determined that the man was List.
   On Dec. 7, 1971, the bodies of List's mother, Alma, 85; his
wife, Helen, 45; and their three children, Patricia, 16, John Jr.
15, and Frederick, 13, were found in their 18-room New Jersey
mansion, after neighbors noticed lightbulbs going out in the home,
police said.
   After the slayings, investigators found that List had two
mortgages on his house, was failing as a financial consultant and
had been siphoning money from his mother's $200,000 savings account.
</TEXT>
