<SECOND>PM-Trump Shuttle,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legal Battle Over Who Must Dump the Name Trump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Donald Trump has won a court order
barring a moving company from calling its service the Trump
Shuttle, although the firm claims the name has nothing to do with
Trump's airline purchase.
   Trump, whose name graces Manhattan towers, Atlantic City casinos
and a very large yacht, on Friday sued International Trading and
Finance Corp. Ltd., which said ``Trump Shuttle'' was the registered
trademark of its moving and storage service for artworks.
   U.S. District Judge Shirley Wohl Kram issued a temporary
restraining order, barring the company from using the disputed name
until at least later this month, when another hearing is scheduled.
   Trump is slated to close a deal next week to buy strikebound
Eastern Airline's shuttle service and plans to re-launch it as the
``Trump Shuttle,'' from New York to Washington and Boston.
   A June 16 hearing will determine if Friday's restraining order
against ITFC should remain in effect until the legal battle is
resolved.
   Fracassi, who has registered the mark Trump Shuttle in New York
state and is seeking federal trademark registration, said earlier
this week that the name is his, and that Trump is the interloper.
   Fracassi said the name stemmed from the company's slogan, ``Play
your trump card _ use the Trump Shuttle.''
   Trump had agreed to purchase Eastern's shuttle in October 1988,
but the deal was held up after Eastern was hit with a crippling
strike in March.
   ITFC registered the trademark in New York in April and filed for
rights to the name with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. The
company is listed in the Washington telephone directory as Trump
Shuttle.
</TEXT>
