<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   06-03 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0453,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's New Government Appointed By Emperor, Convenes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Uno saying his government
not temporary. Pickup 4th graf, `Uno has ...' Minor editing to TRIM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno and his Cabinet today
convened for the first time, but doubts remain whether the public
will be satisfied by what opposition politicians called a stopgap
government.
   Parliament elected Uno as Japan's 47th prime minister Friday to
replace Noboru Takeshita, who resigned because of an
influence-peddling scandal. Uno's appointment ended the governing
Liberal Democratic Party's five-week search for a candidate
untainted by the scandal.
   The new government was formally approved by Emperor Akihito in
an afternoon ceremony at the Imperial Palace in central Tokyo. The
first meeting of Uno's 21-member Cabinet followed at the prime
minister's official residence.
   Opposition political parties and many analysts said they expect
Uno to last only a few months, perhaps departing this summer if the
Liberal Democrats fare poorly in an election expected in July for
half the seats in the upper house.
   During an 80-minute news conference after his first Cabinet
meeting, however, the 66-year-old former foreign minister said he
expected to be a success. ``It is not an interim Cabinet, and I can
tell you that it will be a Cabinet which will be highly
appraised,'' he said.
   Uno said he had changed some of the party practices and declared
that ``all the Cabinet members agreed to put priority on carrying
out various reforms.''
   Asked if he would be influenced in any way by former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, the longtime leader of the party
faction in which Uno was a senior member, Uno reminded reporters he
quit the faction upon assuming the premiership and that Nakasone
resigned from the party because of the scandal.
   ``I highly admire the former prime minister for his achievements
... but I'll do it my own way,'' Uno said.
   Uno has pledged ``a clean start'' for Japanese politics, which
have been stained by the scandal in which Recruit Co., an
information services conglomerate, tried to buy favors from senior
politicians and bureaucrats.
   The most pressing task for Uno will be to reverse low public
approval ratings for his party before next month's elections for
the upper house of parliament. The Liberal Democrats have
controlled both houses of parliament since 1955, but political
observers say the party could lose its hold on government as a
result of the Recruit scandal.
   Uno's choice as party secretary general, Ryutaro Hashimoto, told
reporters on Friday he had received $17,000 in 1985-86 from the
Recruit Co. The new chief Cabinet secretary, Masajuro Shiokawa,
said he gave an unsigned receipt to another Liberal Democrat, who
used it to divide a large donation from Recruit among several
receipts to skirt legal reporting requirements.
   The makeup of the new Uno administration, which contains six of
the same Cabinet ministers who served under Takeshita, ``raises the
strong suspicion that the Liberal Democrats have learned nothing
serious from the Recruit scandal,'' the daily Japan Times wrote in
an editorial today.
   Of the 17 politicians or aides involved in purchases of cut-rate
stock offered by Recruit, 13 were Liberal Democrats.
</TEXT>
