<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0840EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     06-03 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artillery Shells Rain Down On Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners blasted the Christian
heartland with 400 howitzer shells today, and five artillery rounds
crashed into Moslem west Beirut in another violation of a
cease-fire called three weeks ago.
   Police said they could not determine the source of fire on west
Beirut, but the Moslem-run Voice of the Nation radio station blamed
Christian army units of Gen. Michel Aoun. It was the first time
that west Beirut has been shelled since an Arab League cease-fire
was called May 11.
   Although Syrian gunners had been harassing the Christian
heartland with daily shelling, today's barrage was the most severe
in three weeks. It engulfed the coastal stertch north of Beirut,
the presidential palace in suburban Baabda and the nearby Hadath
and Kfar Shima districts.
   No casualties were reported, mainly because most of the shells
crashed into the Christian and Moslem neighborhoods at dawn while
people were indoors.
   An aide to Aoun said, ``We won't remain idle if the cease-fire
violations persist. The general is not prepared to accept the
intensifying shelling.''
   ``We will be forced to fire back,'' he said on condition of
anonymity.
   He denied the army had fired on west Beirut today. He accused
Syrian gunners of hitting the Christians and the Moslems ``so that
our citizens in the western sector would have the impression that
we are shelling them.''
   The aide said Christian gunners would not take any action until
after a meeting Sunday in Casablanca, Morocco, of a committee the
Arab League appointed to seek a solution to the crisis in Lebanon.
   ``Peace will prevail if the leaders adopt a clear decision on
consolidating the cease-fire and lifting the blockades,'' the aide
said. ``If they fail to stop the Syrian violation of the ceae-fire,
then we will have to fire back.''
   The latest round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war
began March 8 when Aoun ordered a blockade of illegal ports run by
Moslem militias south of Beirut. The Syrians and Moslems retaliated
by shelling the Christian heartland, then blockading the
310-square-mile enclave.
</TEXT>
