<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Storm     06-03 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Storm,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornado, Floods Hit Southern Philippines, Kill 11 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thunderstorm spawned flash floods
and a rare tornado that battered villages in the southern
Philippines, killing at least 11 people and forcing thousands to
flee their homes, officials said today.
   The government's Office of Civil Defense said the storm swept
Friday over 12 villages in the coastal areas of Malita in Davao del
Sur province, 650 miles southeast of Manila.
   Gloria Laguidao, a regional civil defense administrator, said
the storm uprooted trees and crops, destroyed 150 houses and two
bridges and killed 11 people. Two people were reported missing and
at least four were hurt.
   Philippine Red Cross officials said four children were among the
dead in Malita, including a 9-day-old baby who drowned when a house
was swept by floodwaters.
   Another infant was accidentally crushed to death by his mother
as she tried to clasp her arms around a tree as the tornado passed.
   Miss Laguidao said the storm forced 650 families, about 3,900
people, to evacuate their homes.
   Malita remains under ``waist-high'' water, she said. The
flooding prevented government relief trucks from reaching the area
after two bridges collapsed.
   ``That tornado was a freak,'' said forecaster Jun Falcon. ``We
seldom get tornadoes here unless there is a sudden drop in
atmospheric pressure.''
   The storm forced rescuers today to halt a search for 21 people
believed trapped in several mine shafts after a landslide and fire
in a gold-mining community on the slopes of Mount Diwalwal in
nearby Davao del Norte province.
   Authorities said at least 11 people died and 21 were reported
missing in the landslide and fire. The blaze also destroyed 180
houses.
</TEXT>
