<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CokeSign 1stLd-Writethru a0438 06-03 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coke Sign, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0438,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Coca-Cola Wall Sign Being Restored</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to identify sign's colors.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY L. CARTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The salesman-artist who painted the first
Coca-Cola wall sign was no Rembrandt, but 95 years later his work
is getting about as much attention from restorers as any
masterpiece.
   Preservationists Alison Free and Aggie Ferguson have put in a
month of painstaking work on the side of Young Brothers Pharmacy in
Cartersville, about 30 miles northwest of Atlanta, to bring to
light what Atlanta-based Coca-Cola executives agree is the first of
its kind.
   Restoring the large red-and-white sign, which says ``Drink
Coca-Cola,'' was the idea of the pharmacy's owner, Dean Cox, who
said townspeople had told him he had a historic treasure under
layers of paint on the store's wall.
   ``I'd heard the rumor for years,'' Cox said, ``and then I
finally got confirmation from Coca-Cola that this was the first
painted wall sign.''
   Coca-Cola representative Randy Donaldson said the original sign
was painted in 1894 by salesman James Couden, who set the precedent
for what later became a standard offer: Sell Coca-Cola in your shop
and the company would paint your wall for free.
   ``Couden was a salesman first and painter next,'' Donaldson said
Friday night, ``so his sign is not quite up to specs. The letters
are kind of squashed.''
   Ms. Free described them as ``chunky'' and said she found another
feature that attests to Couden's amateur status as a painter.
   ``He left the `I' out of drink,'' she said. ``It looks like he
left it out and then stuck it back in there. It's crammed up with
the `N'.''
   She and Miss Ferguson, who operate a restoration company called
Signs of the Times, had a difficult time getting to the point where
they could critique the sign. They said what they had thought would
be a five-day job ended up taking almost 30.
   The task was made difficult because they could not be sure that
the Coca-Cola sign was the first paint put on the brick wall.
   ``If we had taken all the paint off (except the bottom layer) in
the beginning, we could have lost the sign,'' Miss Ferguson said.
   So they used heat guns and spatulas to chip away at a section of
the wall that held a modern Coca-Cola sign. After going through
layer after layer of Coca-Cola advertising, they found the original
sign.
   After the oldest Coca-Cola sign was exposed, the painters worked
at matching the original colors. They plan to repaint it next week.
   The extra work boosted the cost of the restoration project. Cox
said the final bill will be $8,000 to $10,000. He is paying most of
the tab, but Donaldson said Coca-Cola will pay part.
   ``I hope the state will put up a historical marker,'' Cox said.
``But if not, I will or maybe Coca-Cola will.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890603-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0851EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0444 06-03 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0444,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Relaxes, Awaits Response From Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBs 3rd graf pvs Bush was x x x Sunday. with four new grafs
to update with early morning jog. Picks up 4th graf, At an arrival etc....
^By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he brought a
``message of hope'' back from his triumphant weeklong trip to
Europe but says he doesn't expect Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to respond soon to arms control initiatives embraced by
NATO nations.
   ``There's no grand design out there right now now. We just want
to move forward,'' Bush told reporters.
   The president went for an early-morning jog near his oceanside
estate and told reporters he had trouble sleeping, first waking up
at 3 a.m. and then rising at 4:45 a.m.
   The president planned to go fishing today in his boat and was to
meet in the afternoon with Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, and Maine Gov. John S. McKernan.
   Asked if he'd heard yet from Gorbachev, the president shouted as
he jogged past a group of reporters: ``No phone calls yet.''
   He is scheduled to return to Washington on Sunday.
   At an arrival ceremony at nearby Pease Air Force Base in
Portsmouth, N.H., on Friday, Bush declared: ``We must stay on the
offensive. We must now get to work to end the cold war.''
   ``I am now returning from Europe with a message for the American
people _ a message of hope,'' Bush told a jubilant gathering
attended by a welcoming crowd of several thousand invited guests,
many of them schoolchildren. ``We have a great and historic
opportunity to shape the changes that are transforming Europe.''
   Bush, basking in praise from allies of his proposal for dramatic
troop reductions in Europe and for resolving a NATO dispute over
short-range missiles, told reporters on Air Force One shortly
before his arrival that he had not heard directly from Gorbachev on
the proposals.
   He added: ``You don't expect an instant answer. But I'm
confident we will and I hope it's positive.''
   ``It will be a while'' until a formal Soviet response, he
suggested.
   On prospects of a summit meeting this year with the Soviet
leader, Bush said, ``I've always felt that we eventually will get
together and should.''
   But the president gave no clues on when such a meeting might
take place, and dismissed suggestions that he and Gorbachev might
cross paths when Bush returns to Europe next month for the
seven-nation economic summit of industrial democracies in Paris _ a
trip that will also take him to the Warsaw Pact countries of Poland
and Hungary.
   ``I think the first priority is to follow through on the
collective decision that NATO has taken...So we've got some work to
do to make this NATO decision into a reality. But I'm determined to
kick our bureaucracy and the NATO bureaucracy as best I can (to)
push it forward,'' Bush said.
   After arriving in this seacoast resort, the president
immediately headed out into the Atlantic on his 28-foot speedboat,
``Fidelity,'' on a fishing trip _ spending about two hours out
before rain and a smoking engine forced him to return to port. He
pointed gleefully to a mackerel that his fishing party had caught
as he returned to the marina where he keeps his boat.
   Bush had no public appearances planned before he returns to
Washington on Sunday afternoon.
   In his arrival remarks, Bush said his proposal for conventional
arms cuts in Europe, which would include the withdrawal of 30,000
U.S. troops, was ``bold but fundamentally fair.''
   At the summit, Bush proposed a drastic reduction in East-West
conventional forces in Europe and said the cuts should come by 1993.
   At Bush's urging, NATO nations also agreed to a compromise
settlement of a dispute over short-range nuclear missiles that will
enable the weapons to be put on the negotiating table after a
conventional arms deal is completed. The United States and Britain
had voiced skepticism of such negotiations while West Germany
wanted them immediately.
   Bush said the compromise demonstrated that NATO could ``manage
change while remaining true to the strategy of deterrence which has
kept the peace'' for the past 40 years.
   In his talk with reporters on Air Force One, Bush was asked if
he felt his assertiveness in seeking to seize the initiative from
Gorbachev by proposing new disarmament initiatives in Europe had
won him new respect at home.
   Mentioning comedian Rodney Dangerfield, whose complaints about
not getting respect became a classic comedy line, Bush said: ``You
mean, like Rodney Dangerfield kind of thing? I've not suffered from
lack of respect.''
   But Bush allowed that he felt ``pretty good'' about the events
of the past few days.
</TEXT>
