<FIRST>r i PM-AirportAlert 1stLd-Writethru a0489 06-03 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airport Alert, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Stepped Up at Frankfurt Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs after last pvs, ``The spokesman ...'' to ADD charges
about Frankfurt Airport security, background on Flight 103. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have stepped up
security at Frankfurt Airport after receiving indications that
Middle East terrorists may be planning an attack, a spokesman said
today.
   Christian Jalezke, spokesman for the Hesse state Interior
Ministry, said the alert was linked to the sentencing of hijacker
Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, was convicted of murder and
air piracy and sentenced to life imprisonment on May 17 for
hijacking a TWA airliner in June 1985. During the hijacking, U.S.
Navy diver Robert Stethem was shot and killed and 39 Americans were
held hostage for 17 days.
   Less than a week after Hamadi's sentencing, authorities ordered
all airports in the country to tighten security. Jalezke said the
latest alert came after authorities received indications that a
Middle East terrorist group he did not identify may be planning a
retaliatory attack for Hamadi's sentencing.
   He said the information received by authorities focused on a
terrorist action against air traffic. The information lacked
specifics but had to be taken seriously, Jalezke said.
   The spokesman declined to give details about the security
measures taken at Frankfurt Airport, except to say that the number
of policemen guarding continental Europe's busiest airport has been
increased.
   Some British news reports have questioned security at Frankfurt
Airport, where they say the bomb that destroyed Pan Am Flight 103
was planted.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt and switched to a Boeing 747
in London. Investigators say a bomb hidden in a radio-cassette
recorder stored in luggage in the hold destroyed the New York-bound
plane as it flew over Scotland on Dec. 21. The crash killed all 259
people on board and 11 on the ground.
   West German authorities have repeatedly insisted there is no
evidence the bomb was planted in Frankfurt.
</TEXT>
