<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-USAmbassador     06-03 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-US Ambassador,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dean of U.S. Ambassadors Leaves His Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Maxwell Rabb, whose departure was
delayed by the visit of President Bush, said goodbye to Italy today
and left the post he had held for eight years.
   Rabb had intended to leave the assignment May 20 but stayed on
through last week's presidential visit because Peter Secchia, the
Michigan businessman nominated to succeed Rabb, has not been
confirmed by the Senate.
   ``These eight years have seen a tremendous growth in Italy's
stature and importance on the world scene,'' Rabb said in remarks
prepared before his departure early this afternoon.
   ``Together Italy and the United States have resolved many
issues, and I'm proud that I leave Rome with no problems remaining
unresolved on the bilateral agenda,'' he said.
   Rabb also praised Italy's commitment to NATO that he said had
been demonstrated by its acceptance of cruise missiles and its
willingness to accept F-16 fighter bombers that will be expelled
from Spain.
   At the time of his departure, Rabb was the longest-serving U.S.
ambassador at a single overseas post.
   Rabb, who was accompanied by his wife Ruth and seen off by the
U.S. ambassador to the Vatican, Frank Shakespeare, intends to
resume his law practice in New York.
   Secchia's confirmation as Rabb's replacement has been stalled in
the Senate because of a concerns by Sen. Malcolm Wallop, a
Republican from Wyoming.
   Some senators have expressed reservations over Secchia's
qualifications for the job and his use of abrasive, sometimes
profane language in public.
</TEXT>
