<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan     06-03 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan's President Calls For Pragmatic China Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui said today that if
Taiwan wants to regain international recognition it must admit that
the communists rule mainland China.
   Lee's statement was the first public acknowledgment by a
Taiwanese leader that the communists control the mainland.
   He made it at the opening session of a three-day congress of the
governing Nationalist Party, which has ruled Taiwan since the
Nationalists lost the mainland to the communists in a 1949 civil
war.
   ``We should have the courage to face the situation that for the
time being we are unable to exert effective rule over the
mainland,'' Lee told delegates, who included aged Nationalist
officials who fought in the war.
   However, he refused to relinquish the Nationalist claim to the
mainland.
   ``There is only one China and the country will be reunified
eventually. The ultimate goal of our foreign policy is to keep the
nation's sovereignty intact,'' he said.
   Lee also reiterated what is popularly known as Taiwan's ``Three
No'' policy toward the communists _ no official contacts, no
compromise and no talks.
   His address was considered a veiled criticism of the party's
conservative Old Guard, whose refusal to acknowledge communist rule
of China has been blamed for Taiwan's diplomatic isolation.
   Only 23 countries recognize the Nationalists, compared to 136
that have diplomatic ties with China.
   Lee said he believes a more flexible and pragmatic foreign
policy will encourage many countries to ``readjust their
short-sighted China policy'' and recognize his Nationalist
government.
   The Nationalists, he said, continue to support a student-led
democracy movement in China because the protesters ``are linked to
us by blood, in their fight for freedom, democracy and survival.''
   Also today, the party's newly appointed Secretary-General James
Soong told delegates Taiwan never will use force to reunify China.
   ``The reunified China we are seeking shall be guided by the free
will of all the Chinese and the principles of democracy,'' said
Soong.
</TEXT>
