<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Egypt     06-03 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Egypt,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian Vessel Fires On Israeli Fishing Boat, One Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Egyptian naval ship opened fire on an
Israeli fishing boat today as it drew close to Egyptian territory,
Israel radio said. The captain of the fishing vessel was reported
wounded.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, Allon Liel, said Israel demanded
Egyptian authorities explain their actions. ``We don't know exactly
what happened in this case, and we are asking the Egyptians for
details,'' he said.
   The radio said the confrontation occurred this morning near
Coral Island, a popular spot for Israeli divers, off the coast of
Eilat and near the Egyptian beach resort of Taba. The radio said
the Israeli fishing vessel was one mile from shore when an Egyptian
naval craft approached and opened fire.
   The captain of the Israeli vessel was hit in the legs and
stomach, but he managed to pilot his craft back to an Israeli-held
area of the beach. He was rushed to a hospital in the southern
resort city of Eilat, the radio said.
   Liel said Egypt's territorial limits vary in different areas
near Eilat but added that Israeli boats may not anchor or loiter in
Egyptian waters.
   Israel returned Taba, a 250-acre resort to Egypt in March, after
seven years of bitter squabbling over the beach resort.
</TEXT>
