<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103     06-03 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockerbie Gathers For Flight 103 Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people ate hot dogs and
listened to music today at a party thrown for the city where Pan Am
Flight 103 tumbled to earth, but relatives of crash victims said
the good time was in bad taste.
   Ed Blaus, a 14-year-old from Sicklerville, N.J., who suggested
the idea for the party to lift the city's spirits, said he was
surprised to learn the party had been dubbed ``Ed's Party.''
   ``I just want all the kids to come here and enjoy themselves
because they missed Christmas and everyone should have a
Christmas,'' he said.
   A bomb on board Flight 103 exploded over Lockerbie four days
before Christmas, killing all 259 people on the plane and 11 on the
ground. Burning wreckage from the New York-bound Boeing 747
destroyed several Lockerbie homes.
   Relatives of some victims said the party was in poor taste.
   ``I have been talking with a number of those people bereaved by
this outrage and, without exception, they are saying that holding
this party is repugnant and abhorrent,'' Jim Swire, spokesman for
the U.K. Families-Flight 103 group, said today.
   Swire's daughter died in the explosion.
   Blaus, who read about the bombing in the newspapers and in
letters from Lockerbie pen pal David Stewart, said he first wanted
to send presents to Lockerbie, but his idea just grew.
   ``I wrote to Pan Am because I thought that everyone should have
a Christmas, no matter what. I just wanted them to send presents
over and they said they would help me,'' he said.
   ``But it just got bigger and bigger. I never thought it would be
called Ed's Party, but here I am and I am going to eat pizza.''
   Pan Am flew Blaus, his parents and three brothers to Lockerbie.
But Pan Am has said it was not organizing the party.
   Community leader Alex McElroy said the party was supported by
most local people, ``not to cause distress or anguish, but to prove
to themselves and the world that whereas we mourn those who died,
they are determined to repair their town, rebuild shattered lives
and ensure a special and sacred place in their hearts for the 270
people from 24 nations who died.''
   Complaints from relatives of the victims led the Disney
Organization to cancel plans to send Mickey Mouse to the party, and
the Hebrew National company decided against supplying hot dogs.
</TEXT>
