<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     06-03 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Says He May Join Anti-Roh Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KWANGJU, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung said
today he will fight to oust President Roh Tae-woo unless his
government takes steps to bring full democracy to South Korea.
   Kim, head of the largest opposition group, the Party for Peace
and Democracy, also said his talks with Roh, scheduled for later
this month, could be their last meeting.
   ``Let's give the Roh government six more months to solve the
Kwangju issue and implement full democracy. If it still fails to
fulfill the mission, our party will be all out to terminate it,''
Kim told a rally of 100,000 people at a Kwangju college.
   Dissidents are demanding that the government divulge details of
police suppression of a 1980 uprising in Kwangju in which, by
government count, at least 200 people were killed.
   Kim demanded that Roh's predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan, and other
government officials be held responsible for ``the unpardonable
massacre'' in the city.
   Kim's remarks were his strongest challenge to the Roh government
since Kim's party emerged as the No.1 opposition party in the 1988
general elections.
   Kim said the Roh government is backing away from promised
democratic reforms. His speech was interrupted twice as dozens of
radical students protested his party's moderate policies.
   Supporters threw cans and bottles and drove out protesting
students.
   After the two-hour rally, 10,000 people began a march through
downtown streets, shouting slogans for the ouster of the Roh
govenrment. Groups of up to 1,000, hurling rocks, fought police in
the city center for several hours.
   Some people were injured, but police had no overall figures.
   Kim has long been a popular in Kwangju, the capital city of his
home province, South Cholla, but his visit today was marred by
protests over his party's comparatively moderate policies.
   ``No compromise with murderers,'' protesters, mostly students,
shouted as Kim arrived at a cemetery where the bodies of the 1980
Kwangju victims are buried.
   Some protesters threw eggs, water and sand at Kim and party
officials as they arrived at a hospital morgue to pay homage to the
body of a dissident student found dead at a reservoir last month.
The opposition leader was not hit. Authorities announced early this
week that the student, Lee Chol-kyu, 24, died by drowning, but
dissidents claim that he was tortured to death by police.
   In central Seoul, 1,000 radical students and dissidents held a
rally today at Myungdong Cathedral, demanding that authorities
reinvestigate the student's death. They shouted slogans such as
``Down with Roh regime.
</TEXT>
