<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     06-03 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Moslem Group Claims It Bombed U.S. Aid Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown Moslem group
today claimed it planted a small bomb that exploded in front of the
U.S. Agency for International Development.
   The homemade bomb, which caused no injuries, apparently was
intended for the neighboring Indian High Commission.
   Police said it was hurled from a moving vehicle Friday after
riot police fired tear gas and bullets to disperse 500 Moslem
demonstrators trying to march to the Indian High Commission.
   Moslems accuse Indian peacekeeping troops of failing to prevent
clashes between Tamils and Moslems in which at least 13 people were
killed last month. Most Tamils are Hindu, and both groups are
ethnic minorities among the majority Sinhalese Buddhists.
   Newspaper offices today received statements from the Noorul
Islamic Liberation Front claiming responsibility for the bomb.
Police said they have not heard of the group.
   Indian troops were sent to northern and eastern Sri Lanka in
1987 to enforce a peace accord to end a Tamil separatist revolt.
   Moslems accuse the Tamils of trying to force them, as well as
the Sinhalese, out of Eastern Province. The province's population
is equally divided among the three ethnic groups. Tamils account
for 18 percent and Moslems 7 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people.
</TEXT>
