<FIRST>r i PM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru a0483 06-03 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede TROMSOE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope Calls For Reconciliation Of All Christians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE pope arriving in Iceland, pleading for
reconciliation of Christians. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II pleaded for the
reconciliation of all Christians on his arrival today in Iceland,
which has 1,800 Roman Catholics among its mainly Lutheran
population of 244,000.
   Starting the second leg of a five-nation Scandinavian tour in
one of the most unpolluted countries of the world, the pope also
noted that people everywhere are beginning to recognize that the
pursuit of materialism is threatening the environment.
   He also said people throughout the world are increasingly aware
that peace among nations ``can only be the fruit of a just economic
and social order.''
   Prime Minister Steingrimur Hermannsson welcomed him at Keflavik
Airport on a grey and chilly day, saying the pope was received ``as
a true servant of the God in whom we believe, regardless of the
church to which we may belong.''
   Christianity was established as the official church in Iceland
1,000 years ago, but Roman Catholicism was vanquished by the
Protestant Reformation in the 16th century.
   The pope said part of this 24-hour visit to Iceland would ``seek
to encourage the good relations which have developed between
Iceland Catholics and the members of other ecclesial communities.''
   ``Despite the tragic divisions which have long separated
Christians, all of us must try to live in fidelity to the lord's
will, to be instruments of his reconciliation, to maintain the
unity of the spirit in the bond of peace.''
   At the airport, the pope kissed the ground as soon as he stepped
off his plane _ a gesture he makes in every country he visits for
the first time.
   A crowd of youngsters waved Icelandic flags, and the pope kissed
two young girls who presented him with flowers in the red, blue and
white colors of Iceland's flag.
   The pope flew to this northernmost capital in the world, just
below the Arctic Circle, from Tromsoe, Norway, where he extolled
marriage and strong family values in a country where many couples
live together without getting married.
   Police took into custody four people as the pope celebrated Mass
in the market square of Tromsoe, which is 200 miles north of the
Arctic Circle. Two women were detained for protesting closer
relations with the Catholic church, and two men criticized the
Vatican's human rights record.
   Police estimated fewer than 1,000 people attended in one of the
smallest crowds at an open-air Mass on the pope's 42 foreign trips.
   Speaking from a wooden altar, John Paul touched on an issue of
concern to the churches in Scandinavia, where about 50 percent of
the couples never marry and most children today are born out of
wedlock.
   ``The love of a married couple unites them, but it also enables
them to become cooperators with God in giving life to a new person,
'' he said, speaking in English.
   ``Thus they establish the most basic of human communities, the
family,'' which he said was ``a fundamental gift.''
   Catholic officials have complained of the difficulty of
encouraging traditional values in a secular atmosphere.
   John Paul also is visiting Finland, Denmark and Sweden on his
10-day tour. Only about 1 percent of Scandanavians are Catholic.
   Lutheran churches are tax-financed and part of the state
bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890603-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseDivided Bjt   06-03 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Divided, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Under Siege, House Democrats Suspect a Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One congressman compares the atmosphere in the
House these days to the bloody battlefields of World War I ``where
sticking your head out of the trench might get it shot at.''
Another calls up the memory of dirty tricks used by the Nixon White
House to wage political warfare.
   An ``evil wind'' is blowing, says a Democratic chairman, Jack
Brooks of Texas. A Republican, Vin Weber of Minnesota, talks of the
outbreak of ``ethics war.'' Jim Wright, in shedding the
speakership, said ``mindless cannibalism'' had been let loose.
   Last week, House members found that the political ground rules
seemed to be shifting. The underlying habits of accommodation and
accord were giving way to a cut-throat partisanship so intense it
worried some.
   Louis Stokes, D-Ohio, a former ethics committee chairman, said
if the new mood persists ``the end result will be to destroy this
institution as we know it today.''
   Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., said the Republicans should ``stop the
war, if it's that, because the major concern we ought all to have
at this point is the institution.''
   What was new was the prospect of a siege of retribution in the
House: the use of ethics charges as a political tool.
   That's not the tradition. In the past, when the House censured
members for violating the rules, it did so as an institution acting
as a whole against the transgressions of an individual.
   Democrats say they see the hand of newly installed Republican
Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia, Wright's tormentor, behind the
events which put them in disarray last week. Some suspected they
were witness to, and victims of, a campaign that had its
inspiration outside the House.
   ``The fear is that it is in the hands of the Lee Atwaters of the
world,'' said Leon Panetta, D-Calif. ``That's the concern.''
   Atwater, an aggressive political infighter, was a key strategist
in President Bush's campaign last year. Bush installed him as
Republican national chairman and Atwater has set out to end 35
years of Democratic domination of the House.
   Republicans scoff at the cries of foul play. Mickey Edwards of
Oklahoma said in an interview that if there is poison in the air
its source was the heavy-handed tactics by Wright as speaker _
stacking committees, restricting debate, maneuvering the minority
into defeats.
   ``Wright would use the rules in any way he could to manipulate
the outcome of a vote,'' Edwards said. ``Republicans, and many
Democrats, felt that it wasn't just a matter of getting outvoted,
it was a matter of not even having a fair shot.''
   When Wright said last week he was sorry if he had contributed to
the House's bitterness, ``that was ludicrous,'' said Edwards. ``He
was responsible for it more than any human being.''
   But Edwards added that his fellow Republicans may be off on a
dangerous game: ``Republicans have not cornered the market on
morality.''
   And Republican Weber said his party has no appetite for
escalation. ``There is a strong sense that we don't want to start
ethics wars,'' he told The Washington Post. ``I don't expect any
Republicans to file charges against Democrats.''
   On the other hand, Republican Bill Green, N.Y., said ethics is a
legitimate political issue. After all, he said, ``You've had two of
the top three Democrats here resign.''
   ``If the Democrats want to stop what Jim Wright called the
`mindless cannibalism,' the place to begin is to call off their
vendetta against Newt Gingrich,'' said Guy Vander Jagt of Michigan,
chairman of the Republican Congressional Campaign Committee.
   ``The Democrats believe this is a concerted, planned,
coordinated effort,'' said Steny Hoyer, D-Md., of the Republican
hardball. ``It is a continuation of the 1988 campaign.''
   The reference, of course, was to events which caused Wright to
renounce the speakership and his seat after a long ethics
investigation, led the ambitious Rep. Tony Coelho of California,
the No. 3 Democrat, to resign from Congress rather than face an
ethics investigation and led FBI agents to question William H.
Gray, D-Pa., during the Memorial Day weekend about allegations of
financial impropriety.
   The FBI's visit occurred at an awkward time for Gray; seeking to
move up in the Democratic hierarchy, he is a candidate for Coelho's
old job of whip.
   Hoyer said it all brought to mind tactics of the Nixon era:
``The Nixon years showed us the ability to use executive apparatus
in political campaigns.''
   Panetta called up the image of World War I trench warfare. He
said he saw ``a World War I mentality'' at play in the use of
ethics charges to savage the Democrats.
   If the get-even mood prevails, Gingrich stands out as the
Democrats' tempting target. A Democratic irritant in the best of
times, Gingrich is facing an investigation by the ethics committee
on complaints much like those that brought Wright down.
   Members of both sides who want a truce look to the sure-to-be
next speaker, Democrat Thomas Foley of Washington. He was
universally praised as a conciliator, an intellectual, fair-minded
and evenhanded. If he wants to add peacemaker to those accolades,
opportunity awaits his elevation Tuesday to speaker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
