<FIRST>r a AM-SentenceSentence     06-03 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sentence Sentence,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Thief Gets Stiff Sentence: 10,000 Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLEASANTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When convicted car thief Timothy
Loggins walked out of an Alameda County courtroom, he had one
sentence in jail and 10,000 more on paper.
   After Loggins pleaded guilty last year to car theft, Municipal
Court Judge D. Ronald Hyde sentenced him to five weekends in the
county jail and ordered him as part of his probation to write this
sentence 10,000 times:
   ``If I don't own it, I won't take it.''
   This week, the judge ordered Loggins, 20, held without bail in
the jail after he failed to complete the literary assignment,
despite Loggins' sworn claim that he had completed 3,000 sentences.
   Hyde said nothing was produced for the court to see. He also
ordered Loggins to return every day to the
Livermore-Pleasanton-Dublin Municipal Court holding cell to
complete his writing assignment.
   Hyde said that when he last checked Friday, Loggins had
completed about 1,400 sentences.
   Hyde also said Loggins is taking his writing assignment ``in
good spirits'' and will benefit from it.
   ``I want him to feel that this repetitive writing is about as
foolish as what he did,'' Hyde said. ``I want people to know that
if you steal, you're going to pay a price, and it isn't always
jail.''
</TEXT>
