<DOCNO> AP890603-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w FBISendingAgenttoSiteofCrashThatKilledZiaandU.S.Envoy 
   06-03 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>FBI Sending Agent to Site of Crash That Killed Zia and U.S. Envoy</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is sending an agent to the site of the
August plane crash that killed Pakistani President Mohammad Zia
ul-Haq and U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel, an agency official
confirmed.
   The agent will be sent within a week, nearly 10 months after the
FBI was initially shut out of the investigation, said Oliver B.
Revell, executive assistant director for investigations.
   The aim will be to seek evidence at the site where the plane
went down Aug. 17, killing the two officials and 27 others,
including Brig. Gen. Herbert M. Wassom, the chief U.S. defense
representative to Pakistan.
   Pakistan's official report on the crash has been under review by
the FBI since October. It concludes that sabotage was the cause but
does not pinpoint those responsible.
   Revell said the FBI has completed its review of the report.
   ``We have conducted all of our interviews of U.S. participants
and witnesses and we are dispatching an agent to go on-scene to
conduct an on-scene evaluation and we will go from there,'' he said.
   He said the decision to keep the FBI out of the investigation
appears to have come from within the National Security Council.
``The Pakistanis as we understand would have agreed for us to be
there, but it was never presented to them,'' he said.
   ``I personally believe that this was a very unique situation, a
very sensitive location with a U.s. ally teetering on the brink,''
Revell said. ``People who did not know the requirements of the
(anti-terrorism) law made a decision without understanding the
ramifications of the decision.''
   In more recent terrorist incidents, there has been cooperation
between the State Department and the FBI, he said.
   Rep. Bill Hughes, D-N.J., has been critical of the FBI's
exclusion from the investigation, saying it is the only agency with
the expertise to determine whether Zia and Raphel were victims of
terrorism.
   ``Pakistan is one of the key diplomatic posts,'' said Hughes.
``Everybody said right away we couldn't rule out sabotage. A proper
criminal investigation was not carried out, whether for national
security reasons, a turf battle, an understanding with the
Pakistanis or an absolute blunder.''
   Hughes had known Raphel, a native of Atlantic City, N.J., and
highly respected member of the diplomatic corps.
   ``I met Arnold before he went to Pakistan,'' Hughes said. ``He
was probably one of the rising stars.''
   Hughes' crime subcommittee has been trying to determine why the
State Department on Aug. 21 at first granted and then denied the
Federal Bureau of Investigation permission to investigate the crash.
   ``It's not the first time I've seen potential criminal
investigations thwarted,'' Hughes said. ``It's obvious somebody
bungled the job.''
   ``In this instance, nobody brought in any criminal
investigators, no forensics experts, no autopsies were done on the
pilots,'' he said. ``They did find foreign substances on the plane
_ components suitable for a medium-size incendiary device which are
not explained away.''
</TEXT>
