<DOCNO> AP890603-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Khomeini 3rdLd-Writethru a0552 06-03 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Khomeini, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Khomeini Develops Complication After Surgery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 8 grafs of biographical info after last pvs, ``Since then...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, recovering from surgery for bleeding in his digestive
system, has developed a ``complication,'' Tehran radio reported
Saturday.
   The radio gave no details of the deterioration in the
86-year-old spiritual leader's condition but urged the nation to
pray for his recovery.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, contained a statement from
Khomeini's office that said:
   ``At 3:00 p.m. (7:30 a.m. EDT) on Saturday a complication arose
in the Imam's condition, which the doctors are trying to control.
We urge the nation to pray for the Imam's health and hope that
their prayers will be answered.''
   The deterioration in Khomeini's condition followed reports over
the past five days that he was making a normal recovery.
   Khomeini underwent surgery 11 days ago to control intestinal
bleeding.
   A few days after the operation, Tehran television, also
monitored in Nicosia, said a ``slight cardiac complication'' had
arisen, but that it had been relieved the next day.
   Khomeini is referred to by Iranians as the Imam, or spiritual
leader.
   On Thursday, Khomeini was allowed out of bed in a Tehran
hospital and visited with friends and relatives outside the
building, the television said. It showed film of the revolutionary
patriarch sitting outside performing his prayers. The report quoted
doctors as saying Khomeini's condition was ``very satisfactory''
and that he was expected to make a complete recovery.
   Iran's main opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's
Holy Warriors, said in a statement earlier this week that Khomeini
suffered a heart attack last Saturday. The statement said the heart
attack came five days after he underwent surgery on the duodenum,
part of the small intestine close to the stomach. The Mujahedeen's
claim could not be independently confirmed.
   Khomeini reportedly has been ailing since he had a heart attack
in 1986.
   Since then he has rarely been seen outside his home in the north
Tehran suburb of Jamaran.
   Khomeini, the son of a religious leader from a village southwest
of Tehran, taught for years at Qom, the center of Shiite teaching
in Iran.
   He attracted attention for his independent-mindedness and stern
moral example and soon became a focus for opposition to the
monarchy in Iran.
   He was sent into exile in November 1964, first to Turkey, then
to Iraq, where he settled in the Shiite shrine city of Najaf. He
later moved to France.
   Khomeini emerged in 1978 as the moral leader of a burgeoning
revolution against the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi that was
organized through Iran's Shiite clergymen and their followers.
   He returned to Tehran in February 1979 after the Shah fled the
country and became the supreme head of Iran's Islamic revolution
for life.
   Khomeini developed into a skilled politician balancing the
different Iranian factions against each other but never losing his
power as leader of the theocratic state.
   When Iran's eight year war with Iraq ended in a U.N.-sponsored
cease-fire in August, there was speculation Khomeini would back
more moderate members of the Iranian regime in their efforts to
rebuild the war-ravaged country.
   But his radicalism re-emerged in February with a purge of those
members of the hierarchy and a call for the death of British author
Salman Rushdie for his irreverant portrayal of Islam in his novel,
``The Satanic Verses.''
</TEXT>
