<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1458EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ProfessorPoetry     06-03 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Professor Poetry,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ballots Cast, Winner Found; It's Seamus Heaney, Oxford Bound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oxford graduates in their black academic
robes gathered among the university's ancient spires on Saturday
and elected Irish poet Seamus Heaney to the prestigious post of
professor of poetry.
   Heaney, an award-winning poet and favorite of the university's
arts establishment, was born in Northern Ireland and lives in
Dublin and the United States, where he is a professor at Harvard
University. He is 50.
   None of the poets was present when the announcement was made
outside the university's divinity school.
   Heaney, who won 316 of the 485 total votes cast Thursday and
Saturday, had always been heavily favored for the professorship,
one of the university's least arduous posts. It requires three
lectures for each of its five years.
   Heaney could not be reached for comment. Telephone calls to his
office in Boston went unanswered, and his home telephone number was
not listed.
   The highly regarded and popular poet was nominated by Oxford
novelist Dame Iris Murdoch, by three previous holders of the
professorship and by Oxford's most influential English literature
specialists.
   In addition to his poetry, Heaney has published books of
literary criticsm and has long experience teaching. A member of the
Irish Academy of Letters, he became Boylston Professor of Rhetoric
and Oratory at Harvard, in Cambridge, Massachusetts, in 1985.
   Competition for the professorship, though dignified, has been
intense.
   Charles H. Sisson, a 75-year-old poet, author and translator was
a notable contender and garnered 96 votes.
   An attention-getting outsider was 30-year-old Rastafarian reggae
poet Benjamin Zephaniah, who was a candidate for the post of writer
in residence at Cambridge University's Trinity College in 1986 and
only narrowly missed.
   He had the backing of younger graduates but, as columnist Andrew
Brown wrote in The Independent newspaper: ``Dialect is notoriously
difficult to transliterate in English ... (so) his work looks no
more than silly on paper, but that is not how he is to be judged.''
   ``He is said to be very impressive in live performance,'' Brown
added.
   Zephaniah won 60 votes.
   He was followed by Duncan McCann, with nine votes. McCann lost
to current professor Peter Levi five years ago.
   McCann was so indignant at being referred to as ``the barroom
poet'' because of his nomination by friends from The King's Arms in
Oxford that some papers took to calling him ``not the barroom
poet.''
   In addition to the three lectures the poetry professor gives
each year, he must judge three English poetry and essay
competitions for students and give a public oration every other
year.
   From the establishment of the professorship in 1708 until 1972,
the oration had to be delivered in Latin _ a task which alone might
merit the professor's annual stipend of $4,960.
   But in 1972 Roy Fuller got away with delivering his in English
and successors have followed suit. Levi delivered his last oration
in verse.
   Previous sitters in the illustrious poetry chair have included
W.H. Auden, Robert Graves and Edmund Blunden.
</TEXT>
