<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     06-03 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kabul Rocket Attack Kills 5; 100 Reported Killed In Other Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas killed five people
and wounded six in a rocket attack on Kabul on Saturday, and 100
more people were killed in fighting in the cities of Jalalabad and
Kandahar, the government said.
   It urged Prime Ministr Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan to use her
trip to Washington this week to persuade the United States to cut
off arms supplies to the guerrillas and help negotiate an end to
the 11-year-old Afghan war.
   The attack on Kabul started early Saturday, with one rocket
hitting near a kindergarten, then continued through the night in
one of the most intense attacks in more than a month.
   Military observers said the rockets were fired from the
surrounding hills and appeared to be within close range, but they
could not give the distance. The armed forces responded by firing
artillery and machine guns into the hills. The 12 rockets that fell
Saturday raised to 23 the number that have hit Kabul since
Thursday, the Foreign Ministry said. Twelve people were killed and
13 wounded in the earlier attacks, ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi
Amani said.
   He said fighting between the guerrillas and forces of the
Soviet-backed government occurred in the besieged eastern city of
Jalalabad and the southern city of Kandahar and that at least 100
people died and 36 were injured.
   The report could not be independently verified.
   Before Saturday, the insurgents, who are based in Pakistan, had
said an attack on Kabul was imminent. But Amni scoffed at their
claims, saying the fractious resistance was incapable of mounting a
real offensive on the city.
   ``Some time ago, they said they would carry out an extensive
attack on Kabul. But they have been unable to carry this out. A
rocket fired from 25 miles away cannot be considerd an attack,'' he
said.
   The guerrilla's rockets, with a range of 15-35 miles, are
generally fired by remote control from the mountains that ring the
city. They often land in residential areas rather than hitting
military or government intallations.
   Amani said four civilians were killed and six wounded in
Jalalabad, a city 75 miles east of Kabul that has been under a
guerrilla siege March 7. Afghan soldiers killed 72 guerrillas and
injured 21 in an operation to clear the insurgents from the city
and the areas near the airport, Amani said.
   In the southern city of Kandahar, once Afghanistan's
second-largest city, one civlian was killed and two injured by
rockets, he said. Government troops retaliated by attacking rebel
positions 20 miles from the city and killing 23 guerrillas and
wounding seven, he said.
   Elsewhere, five rockets slammed into the southern garrison town
of Khost, Amani said, but there were no casualties.
   Amani urged the Bush administration to reconsider its policy
toward Afghanistan and cut off the flow of weapons to the
guerrillas.
   ``The Afghan government hopes a policy change will be made
during Ms. Bhutto's visit to United States this week,'' he said.
   Ms. Bhutto has called for a political settlement to the Afghan
war but also has said peace talks should not include members of the
ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   President Najib recently has stepped up his call for peace talks
and offered to negtotiate with the opposition and its Western
backers without conditions.
   ``Why does the United States not help restore peace instead of
supplying more arms to the enemy,'' Amani said. ``Is a country that
calls itself an advocate of human rights to act like this? We
consider this irresponsible.''
   The United States has said it will continue to supply weapons to
the guerrillas as long as the Soviet Union continues to aid Najib's
government.
</TEXT>
