<SECOND>AM-Germany-Protest,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Detain 21 as Leftists Demonstrate Against Far-Right</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police detained 21 people as leftist
demonstrators hurled eggs, tomatoes, stink bombs and paint at about
1,000 supporters of an extreme right party.
   The protest occurred during an election rally of the German
People's Union, whose views often are compared to the Nazis.
   Party candidates for June 18 elections to the European
Parliament are calling for foreigners to be driven out of West
Germany. The party also opposes most European Community policies.
   About 1,000 leftists tried to disrupt the rally and 2,000
police, fearing large-scale clashes, separated the two groups.
Authorities said there were no major incidents.
   In West Berlin, police said they arrested nine neo-Nazi
skinheads after about 150 battled police with bottles and stones
following a soccer match late Friday.
   The skinheads shouted Nazi slogans during the match and later
fought police in a street near the stadium. Police said they
suspect the same group vandalized two subway stations after the
match.
