<FIRST>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0586 06-03 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0586,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Seven in Attack on Palace Guards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE casualties, details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas bombed a bus carrying
Government Palace guards through downtown Saturday, killing at
least seven soldiers and police and wounding 24 other people,
authorities said.
   A car blocked the bus while it was en route to the palace,
police said. Two people maneuvered a pushcart loaded with
explosives under the back of the bus then detonated the cargo, they
said.
   The bus was carrying 42 people, mostly soldiers.
   Police said at least six soldiers and a policeman were killed in
the bombing. They said at least 24 were wounded, including soldiers
and bystanders.
   The guards let off a hail of gunfire but the suspects escaped,
police said on condition of anonymity.
   The government of President Alan Garcia, who lives at the
palace, is fighting two leftist guerrilla organizations, the
Mao-inspired Shining Path and the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement.
   No group claimed responsibility for Saturday's attack.
</TEXT>
