<FIRST>r w AM-Adams-Tupper 1stld-writethru a0533 06-03 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Adams-Tupper, 1st ld-writethru, a0533,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to show Tupper pursued meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors declined to charge Sen.
Brock Adams, D-Wash., with sexual assault because the young woman
involved acknowledged that she pursued a meeting with him that
night and did not leave after he made sexual advances, according to
a newly released letter.
   The prosecutors also cited a lack of physical evidence or
corroborating testimony for her account.
   In response to a Freedom of Information Act request by The
Associated Press, the U.S. Attorney's office released a copy a
Sept. 1, 1987 letter explaining the outcome to Lawrence Baskir,
attorney for Kari Tupper.
   The letter was signed by Charles H. Roistacher, executive
assistant to then-U.S. Attorney Joseph DiGenova.
   A former legislative aide and the daughter of longtime Adams
family friends, Ms. Tupper, now 27, said in September of last year
that Adams, now 62, had drugged and fondled her March 27, 1987 in
his Washington, D.C., home while his wife was away.
   Ms. Tupper said she had accepted an invitation to go to a
restaurant with Adams after determining to tell the senator to stop
propositioning her.
   Adams has denied all her allegations but said he made a mistake
letting her spend the night at his house.
   Roistacher wrote Baskir:
   ``She told the police that she has known Senator Adams for many
years as a family friend. She said that Senator Adams made sexual
overtures toward her for several weeks, if not longer.
Nevertheless, she arranged to have dinner alone with him. When he
did not appear, she drove alone to his house, arriving after dark.
   ``There she had several drinks, and by her account, remained in
his house and had another drink even after his conversation became
explicitly sexual. She went to the bathroom and recalls wondering
whether ...(name deleted by the government to protect privacy of
third party) would learn that she had been there. She recalls
little else, except that she awoke the following morning to find
that someone had removed her clothing....Senator Adams, she said,
was lying by her side, fondling her.''
   Roistacher added that she did not report the incident to police
for three days, declined to identify her assailant until June and
gave differing statements to police.
   Of the drugging allegation, Roistacher said, ``No objective
evidence supports your supposition about the drugging except Ms.
Tupper's symptoms the morning after, which seem equally consistent
with excess consumption of alcohol over the course of an evening.''
A hospital test the day after showed no evidence of drugging.
   Although Baskir had claimed her account was corroborated,
Roistacher replied, ``This `abundant' evidence does not consist of
eyewitness testimony about the crime, nor of physical, scientific
or medical evidence, but the subsequent repetition of her story to
close friends and relatives.''
</TEXT>
