<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 4thLd-writethru a0603 06-03 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 4th Ld-writethru, a0603,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: To show meeting with senators over, subs grafs 11-15 with nine
grafs, ``Bush met''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP White House Correspondent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Saturday he
deeply deplored the military crackdown in China that resulted in
the deaths of peaceful demonstrators and he urged Beijing's
government to return to non-violent tactics in dealing with
pro-democracy protestors.
   ``We have been urging and continue to urge non-violence,
restraint,'' Bush said. ``Tragically another course has been
chosen.''
   ``Again, I urge a return to non-violent means for dealing with
the current situation,'' the president said. Bush made his remarks
in a written statement issued from his vacation home here.
   Bush, who arrived here Friday from a week-long European trip,
did not make any public appearance but was kept abreast of
developments in China by Robert Gates, his deputy national security
adviser.
   He also consulted by telephone with Secretary of State James A.
Baker III in Washington.
   ``It is clear that the Chinese government has chosen to use
force against Chinese citizens who were making a peaceful statement
in favor of democracy. I deeply deplore the decision to use force
against peaceful demonstrators and the consequent loss of life,''
Bush said.
   The president said the United States and China had built a
``constructive relationship'' during the past 20 years through
``great efforts by both sides.''
   The president added that the relationship had been beneficial to
both nations. ``I hope that China will rapidly return to the path
of political and economic reform and conditions of stability so
that this relationship, so important to both our peoples can
continue its growth.''
   After returning from London on Friday, Bush and his wife Barbara
spent the day at their seaside estate with their daughter Dorothy
and her children, Sam and Ellie.
   After an early morning jog, Bush spent a quiet day with no
public appearances. He had endured a night of fitful sleep because
of jetlag.
   Bush met at his seaside home with Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, and Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine. They were
accompainied by Maine Gov. John McKernan and his wife, Rep. Olympia
Snowe, R-Maine.
   Stopping by a cluster of reporters at a checkpoint near Bush's
compound, the two senators praised Bush's statement on China,
saying they supported him.
   Asked if there was anything more the United States could do,
Cohen said ``I think `deplore' and coming from the president is
pretty strong language.''
   Mitchell said, ``I do believe that there can be no justification
for the actions by the Chinese government and the use of force
against its own citizens peacefully demonstrating for the most
basic freedoms and I support _ I strongly support _ the president's
deploring of that violence.''
   ``We ought to make it very clear the U.S. government stands
with, and in support of, those who seek freedom and democracy in
China and throughout the world,'' Mitchell said.
   Mitchell, who had criticized Bush in recent weeks for moving too
slowly in responding to initiatives from Moscow, also praised the
Bush's NATO proposal to cut American and Soviet combat troops in
Europe. Asked if he regretted his earlier criticism, Mitchell said
there was nothing to regret.
   ``We're pleased he took our advice and is now moving fast,''
Mitchell said.
   European leaders hailed Bush as seizing the initiative from
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   At a NATO meeting that concluded last Tuesday, Bush also helped
engineer a compromise to a dispute over East-West negotiations on
short-range nuclear missiles. The agreement stipulates that no
negotiations will be held until the signing of an agreement to
reduce conventional forces and the reductions are already underway.
   During his morning jog, Bush was asked whether he had heard from
Gorbachev. ``No phone calls yet,'' he replied.
   Bush, who returned to the United States from a week-long
European trip, awoke at 3 a.m. EDT and finally got up a 4:45 a.m.
Usually he arises between 6 a.m. and 6:30 a.m.
   His dog, Millie, accompanied him on the 20-minute run.
   New England has been hit by its worst mosquito attack in 30
years, and the bugs were out in force during his run. Secret
Service agents and reporters who watched Bush spent much of their
time swatting the bugs. Bush did not appear to be troubled by them.
   After breakfast, the president went fishing for several hours on
his speedboat, ``Fidelity.'' He briefly climbed aboard a Coast
Guard patrol boat and put on a cap they gave him.
   Bush told reporters he also planned to play tennis during the
day.
   The president will return to Washington Sunday evening.
</TEXT>
