<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallTrial     06-03 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Must Decide What Congressman Knew About Money Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For jurors in the two-week-old perjury trial of
former Republican Rep. Pat Swindall, a familiar question is taking
shape: What did he know, and when did he know it?
   At issue is what Swindall knew about money broker ``Mike
Martinez'' _ actually undercover Internal Revenue Service Agent
Michael Mullaney _ and where Martinez claimed he got his money.
Swindall negotiated with the agent for $850,000 for home
construction over one month in 1987.
   Swindall is accused in the 10-count indictment of lying to a
federal grand jury in February 1988. Under the cloud of the
indictment, he lost his bid for a third term to Democrat Ben Jones,
onetime star of the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' television show, last
November in a district in Atlanta's suburbs.
   If convicted, he faces 10 months to five years in prison on each
count.
   The jury in the case has heard audio tapes and seen videotapes
in which Swindall, at various times, acknowledged that drugs were
the likely source of the money ``Martinez'' had.
   In those conversations, Mullaney also told Swindall that the
deal involved ``washing'' of cash, and the congressman proposed
receiving the money through a mortgage company created for the
purpose by Swindall associate Charles LeChasney, a Cuban emigre who
has since been convicted of money laundering.
   The tapes are the backbone of the government's case, as
prosecutors try to prove that Swindall lied when he testified he
did not recall discussing the illegal nature of the money handling
and that he didn't recall being told the money was narcotics money,
among other allegations.
   Swindall's lead attorney, Richard Hendrix, says he will prove
that LeChasney was ``psychotic liar'' who deceived Swindall into
thinking the deal for $850,000 from Mullaney was all right, while
deceiving the agent into thinking Swindall was a crook.
   In cross-examination over three days last week, Hendrix hammered
at Mullaney over statements the agent himself made in the tapes.
Mullaney told Swindall at one point the money was ``flight
capital,'' then said at another point that it was not and ``could
be anything.''
   Flight capital is money sent out of troubled areas by wealthy
people seeking to invest or store it in a stable country like the
United States.
   And more than two dozen times, Hendrix forced Mullaney to
concede that he did not know what kind of tale LeChasney was
telling Swindall.
   Mullaney, the government's first witness in the case, was on the
stand more than six days, going one-by-one over tapes of 16
conversations he had with LeChasney about the Swindall deal, plus
five with the congressman himself and two meetings with both men.
   Tapes the jury saw or heard include one of a meeting between the
three on Sept. 13, 1987, at a posh West Virginia resort,
``Martinez'' told Swindall ``clearly, I violate some currency
laws,'' and ``my gut feeling is there has to be narcotics dollars
in there. ... It is not flight capital.''
   ``Anything you tell me is told in total confidence,'' Swindall
replied.
   Later, Swindall said, ``I am basically using Charles as my
buffer. ... What I have to say is, I borrowed money from
Gulfstates,'' LeChasney's company.
   On Sept. 23, Swindall indicated he knew LeChasney would handle
the cash in circumvention of bank reporting laws.
   ``Charles is going to ensure that basically the money is
funneled in a way so that there are no reports filed,'' Mullaney
said.
   ``Yeah. I'm protected that way,'' Swindall replied.
   Finally, as the deal collapsed on Sept. 26, Swindall told the
agent he would ``acknowledge'' an ``assignment'' of assets through
LeChasney to Martinez, but he could not accept the cash directly,
because ``I would then be laundering y'all's money.''
   But Hendrix, in cross-examination, repeatedly asked Mullaney why
he had misled the congressman when he told him flatly the money
``is flight capital.''
   ``As opposed to being laundered out of some drug scheme,''
Swindall said.
   ``I would assume so,'' the agent replied.
   Mullaney testified that he was portraying a drug-money
launderer, and such a person would fudge details of the deal when
talking on the telephone.
