<FIRST>r a AM-BridgeCollapse     06-03 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Collapse,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divers Pull Car from River, Find Body Inside</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car believed to have plunged into the Great
Miami River when a temporary bridge collapsed was pulled from the
river Saturday with a body inside.
   The body was the second found in the river since the May 26
collapse of the one-lane, temporary U.S. 52 bridge. The body of
Helen C. Zorn, 52, of the Cincinnati suburb of Green Township, was
found floating in debris Tuesday about five miles downriver from
the bridge.
   Hamilton County authorities said this week that Mrs. Zorn's
daughter, Terry Siemon, 27, was believed to have been with Mrs.
Zorn when the bridge collapsed.
   Sheriff's officers, however, could not immediately confirm that
the body recovered Saturday was that of Ms. Siemon, even though the
car was identified as the one occupied by the mother and daughter,
said sheriff's spokesman Frank Weikel.
   The body was taken to the Hamilton County coroner's office in
Cincinnati for identification, Weikel said.
   Professional divers working with a crane operator about 75 yards
down river from the collapsed bridge located the submerged car. The
crane then dragged it out of the water.
   Later in the day, heavy rain began falling on the site 12 miles
west of Cincinnati, and the search for more victims was called off
for several days until the river level drops back down, Weikel said.
   Strong underwater currents during the past week have frustrated
recovery efforts, which prompted Sheriff Simon Leis Jr. to hire
divers who have experience in underwater investigation at accident
sites.
   Searchers using a sonar imaging device have been unable to find
a second vehicle, either a van or pickup truck, that two witnesses
reported seeing fall from the bridge.
   ``There are no missing-person reports that came in on the van
that supposedly went down, so we're beginning to think there was no
van,'' Weikel said.
</TEXT>
