<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-03 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Spawn Tornadoes, Hail in Midwest, Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First name Toney in 9th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Powerful thunderstorms spawned tornadoes, winds up to 60 mph,
hail and heavy rain in the nation's midsection Saturday, damaging
homes and flooding streets.
   Thunderstorms or showers fell in Michigan, Ohio, Indiana,
Illinois, Wisconsin, Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi, Kansas,
Oklahoma and Texas.
   In Indiana, a tornado near Delong overturned several house
trailers, slightly injuring three people, and downed trees and
power lines, the Fulton County Sheriff's Department said.
   Another twister touched down briefly in Mishawaka, damaging four
trailers, collapsing a vacant municipal storage building and
downing several power poles, officials said. There were no
injuries, but damage was estimated at $500,000.
   Hail as big as golf balls fell and winds gusted to 60 mph.
   Two tornadoes were reported in Henry County, Ohio, and two to
three twisters touched down in Tulia, Hale and Anahuac, Texas.
There were no reports of heavy damage or injuries.
   In Michigan, thunderstorms generated winds gusting to 60 mph
that downed power lines and several trees in Monroe. Two inches of
rain fell in less than 30 minutes in Brownstown Township, flooding
streets.
   A flash flood watch was in effect for a large section of west
Texas.
   On Friday night, thunderstorm winds clocked at nearly 60 mph in
Lincoln, Neb., blew over a 126{-foot section of a replica of the
Vietnam War memorial in Washington, D.C., said Toney Redman. The
replica, called the Moving Wall, and some metal supports were
damaged.
   Driving rain and high winds in Eagle, Neb., forced the
cancellation of a rock concert by the Beach Boys and Chicago.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell Saturday in southern
Florida. Cloudy skies and scattered showers stretched from the
central High Plains to Nevada.
   Heavier rainfall during six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included
nearly 2 inches at Fort Wayne, Ind., and 1\ inches at Fort Smith,
Ark.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees in Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 98 degrees in Alice,
Cotulla and Laredo, Texas, and in Savannah, Ga.
   The low for the 48 contiguous states was 33 degrees in Craig,
Colo., and Flagstaff, Ariz.
   The forecast for Sunday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the northern Rockies and Nevada to the Great
Plains and the Atlantic Coast, with showers and thunderstorms most
likely along a cold front from eastern Idaho and southern Montana
to the central Great Plains and the upper Ohio Valley, and over
Maine. Sunny skies were expected over the Great Lakes region, the
upper Mississippi Valley, the Southwest and the Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 60s from the northern
Rockies and northern Nevada to the northern and central Rockies, in
the upper Great Lakes and northern Maine; in the 90s in Southern
California, southern Arizona and southern Texas and from Florida to
southeastern Virginia; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere in the
nation.
</TEXT>
