<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CommonFuture 2ndLd-Writethru a0569 06-03 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Common Future, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0569,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Global Telecast on Environment Aims to Recruit, Motivate the Masses</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-11, `Among the ..., to UPDATE with entertainers'
performances and leaders' statements. Picks up at dash; material below
dash should stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Combining pep rally spirit and a serious
message, a global telecast aimed at more than 1 billion people
brought celebrities and world leaders together Saturday to push for
a new age of environmental consciousness.
   Called ``Our Common Future,'' the five-hour telecast originated
from New York and picked up satellite feeds from London, Moscow,
Australia, Brazil, Tokyo, Poland and elsewhere.
   Organizers said it was beamed to 100 countries, making it
potentially available to 90 percent of the world's television sets.
   Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland was host of the
collage of music and messages calling for the world to adopt
``sustainable development,'' to reach a happy medium between
improving living standards and protecting resources and the
environment for the future. Mrs. Brundtland chaired a United
Nations commission that developed a report, also called ``Our
Common Future,'' on the same topic.
   ``We need more people to be aware,'' Mrs. Brundtland said as she
opened the broadcast.
   In London, rock musician Bob Geldof quoted Albert Einstein as he
urged viewers to adopt the program's message.
   ``Everything has changed but the way we think,'' Geldof said.
``The first thing we have to change is the way we think.''
   Organizers say the spectacle was not a fund-raiser but a
consciousness-raiser, designed to take advantage of growing concern
over ozone depletion, global warming, tropical rain forest
destruction and other issues.
   ``It's a kind of wake-up call,'' said singer John Denver, one of
the participants.
   Among the other musicians to perform were Stevie Wonder, Elton
John, Sting, Diana Ross, Bob Geldof and Herbie Hancock. Film stars
Richard Gere, Christopher Reeve and Sigourney Weaver and former
Brazilian soccer great Pele also appeared.
   In taped messages, U.S. President George Bush and other world
leaders called for a coordinated international approach to
environmental problems.
   ``We have the talents and resources to advance civilization,''
Bush said. ``Our scientists are probing the mysteries of the
universe. Surely we can apply that same creativity, the same
industry and perseverance, to protect the environment of the one
Earth we all share. We just need the will to do it.''
   In a last-minute arrangement, the show included a live feed from
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's address Saturday to the lower
chamber of the new Supreme Soviet legislature. Gorbachev spoke of
improving efficiency in the use of money and resources ``for
ecological purity.''
   Chinese Premier Li Peng also made a pre-taped statement, calling
for a collective international effort to solve global warming and
other problems. The statement was made before Sunday's deadly
clashes in Tiananmen Square, in which Chinese troops ousted
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Other leaders whose taped comments were broadcast included U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and
Zimbabwean Prime Minister Robert Mugabe.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Hal Uplinger and Tony Verna, who produced and directed the Live
Aid benefit for African relief in 1985, teamed up again for the
telecast. The Swiss-based Centre for Our Common Future and
Washington-based Uplinger Enterprises put it together.
   ``To hold this kind of event lays the foundation of public
awareness,'' said Warren H. Lindner, executive director of the
center. ``You know and I know that political change comes not in
and of itself but is greatly facilitated by an informed and
motivated public.''
   The budget was just under $2 million, which is being covered by
corporate sponsors, Lindner said. All the entertainers donated
their talents, as did many other professionals and technicians
involved.
   Setting up the satellite links and other organizational tasks
were similar to the Live Aid program, which was held in two outdoor
sports stadiums in the United States and Britain, he said.
   The difference is in the participants. Live Aid was virtually
all music and had Irish rock musician Geldof as its host.
   ``It's been a very, very difficult situation,'' Uplinger said.
``You have heads of state involved. You can't do the same things
with Mrs. Brundtland as you can do with Bob Geldof.''
   Mrs. Brundtland chaired a U.N.-appointed commission that spent
three years gathering testimony and information to compile a report
on the world's environment and development. The report was also
called ``Our Common Future.''
   She received the 1988 Third World Prize from the London-based
Third World Foundation for her work of the commission.
</TEXT>
