<FIRST>r a AM-SeabrookProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0584 06-03 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Rally Against Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE that rally largest in 11 years,
include details, quotes; CORRECT that May 1977 protest was at Seabrook
site, sted at gates; picks up 9th graf, `Before the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 anti-nuclear activists
Saturday staged the biggest rally against the Seabrook nuclear
plant in 11 years, a prelude to a civil disobedience protest
planned for Sunday.
   Traffic lined a highway that runs by the seaside plant, and many
of the cars sported anti-Seabrook signs. At Hampton Beach State
Park, less than two miles from the plant, protesters heard speakers
denounce Seabrook and promise to continue fighting to prevent it
from operating commercially.
   Seabrook opponent Steve Comley drew cheers when he told the
gathering he had hired planes pulling anti-nuclear banners to fly
over the beach Saturday and about 40 miles up the Maine coast to
President Bush's home at Kennebunkport, Maine, on Sunday. Bush was
spending the weekend there.
   ``The nuclear industry and some of the people in Washington
believe this fight is over,'' Comley said. ``I'll tell you, we're
just starting.''
   The anti-nuclear Clamshell Alliance is organizing the protests,
which it hopes will be the biggest since May 1977, when 1,414
people were arrested at the Seabrook site. About 2,500 arrests have
been made in protests at the plant since construction began in 1976.
   Saturday's rally had the largest turnout since a 1978 protest
that drew an estimated 18,000 people.
   Officials in neighboring Massachusetts also have sought to block
the plant by refusing to cooperate with emergency evacuation
planning. Despite the opposition, Seabrook won its low-power
testing license from federal regulators on May 26, nearly three
years after the $6 billion reactor was completed.
   Plant officials have begun preparing for the first atomic chain
reaction by Tuesday or Wednesday, plant spokesman Ron Sher said.
   Sher, who stopped by the rally, said the protesters represented
a ``vocal minority.''
   ``But the majority of people in New Hampshire, Massachusetts and
the rest of New England recognize that nuclear power is a viable
energy alternative and Seabrook ... is ready to produce electricity
and it can make an important contribution,'' Sher said.
   The plant first must win federal approval for evacuation plans
for crowded summer beaches and communities up to 10 miles away.
   ``The truth is you cannot evacuate Hampton Beach and the other
beaches and protect the people,'' attorney Robert Backus, who has
represented anti-Seabrook groups since 1972, told the crowd.
   ``The truth is we don't know what to do with nuclear waste,''
Backus said. ``The truth is that the plant is uneconomic.''
   Before the weekend, at least 300 to 500 people went through
training sessions on non-violent civil disobedience, Clamshell
spokesman Paul Gunter said. The sessions continued Saturday.
   On Sunday, some activists planned to climb fences surrounding
the 715-acre plant site and others planned to sit down outside
gates. Some protesters also planned to go to a railroad siding at
the plant to re-create an August 1976 protest in which 18 people
were arrested _ the first group civil disobedience against a U.S.
nuclear power plant.
   Earlier in the week, Superior Court Judge Vincent Dunn let the
town charge the organizers a $300 fee and $3,600 bond for an
assembly permit. Clamshell members said they couldn't and wouldn't
pay.
   Since a town ordinance bars gatherings of more than 25 people
without a permit, the activists said they planned to march to the
plant on Sunday in groups of fewer than 20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
