<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     06-03 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest Raids by Jewish Settlers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Israelis, some carrying
signs saying ``Thou shalt not kill!'' on Saturday protested attacks
by Jewish settlers on Arab communities in the occupied territories.
   Also Saturday, Israeli troops wounded 13 Palestinians in clashes
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials
said.
   In Tel Aviv's Kings of Israel Square, about 30,000 supporters of
a leftist peace coalition held the protest rally against violence
by Jewish settlers.
   Israel television said rally organizers were distributing
petitions, already signed by 32 of Parliament's 120 members,
calling on police and the army to arrest settler vigilantes.
   ``If Israel does not get up and stop them now, maybe some day
not far from now, they (the settlers) will arrest us,'' said
Israeli author Amos Oz.
   The Israeli news media said Saturday the army is considering
restricting the movement of settlers suspected of involvement in
vigilante acts against Palestinians.
   About 70,000 Jews live in 131 settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip that have an Arab population of 1.7 million.
   In the Gaza Strip Israeli soldiers shot and wounded eight
Palestinians, including an 11-year-old boy who was hit in the leg,
Arab hospital officials reported.
   They said that in the West Bank troopers shot and wounded five
Palestinians and one of the victims was a 7-year-old boy.
   The army announced an indefinite curfew on Gaza beginning Sunday
morning, restricting the seaside strip's 700,000 residents to their
homes.
   Palestinian militants launched an uprising against Israeli
occupation in December 1987 and since then at least 504 Arabs have
been killed in the violence. Twenty-two Israelis have been killed.
