<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0600 06-03 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Reject President's Bid for Talks But End Travel
Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with rebels rejecting president's
offer to talk; pickup 7th graf pvs ```All highways...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels on Saturday
spurned the new rightist president's proposal for dialogue,
dismissing it as a call to capitulate.
   The rejection came in a communique from the rebels' Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front broadcast on local radio stations.
There was no immediate reaction from the government.
   Despite their rejection of the offer to talk, the guerrillas
also said Saturday that they lifted a ban on road travel called to
protest the inauguration Thursday of the President Alfredo
Cristiani.
   Cristiani on Friday called for more regional efforts to end El
Salvador's civil war. He said bringing peace to this country was
just as important as dismantling the U.S.-supported Nicaraguan
rebels.
   He has pledged not to negotiate changes in the political system
with the rebels but has offered talks instead on integrating them
into civilian life.
   In their statement, the rebels said they stood ready to
negotiate a political solution to their nine-year war against the
U.S.-backed government. But they said Cristiani's proposal did not
offer them a chance to do so and that it was an ``invitation to
surrender.''
   The rebel communique instead invited El Salvador's political
parties to sponsor a peace dialogue.
   The rebels said the new president had been trying to project
``an image acceptable to the United States and the European
community, but the content of his speech was predominantly
confrontation, strictly faithful to the politics and economics of
Arena.''
   Arena is Cristiani's rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance.
The party takes a hard line on the war, and many observers expect
the fighting to intensify under the Arena government.
   About 70,000 people, mostly civilians, have already died in the
civil war.
   Cristiani assumed power from President Jose Napoleon Duarte, a
Christian Democrat. Duarte is suffering from cancer and has left
the country for more chemotherapy.
   The rebels' traffic ban had paralyzed nationwide traffic since
Wednesday.
   ``All highways are reopened to the free circulation of
vehicles,'' said the rebel Radio Venceremos in Saturday's
broadcast. It said the rebels also ordered all guerrilla units ``to
suspend any further action'' against motorists.
   Guerrillas damaged or destroyed five vehicles and dynamited
power transformers and electrical transmission towers, but no
injuries were reported. The country's 245 gas stations were also
forced to remain closed for fear of rebel reprisals.
   Speaking at his news conference Friday, Cristiani reiterated
accusations made by Duarte that Nicaragua's ruling leftist
Sandinista regime was helping the Salvadoran guerrillas. The
Sandinistas have often denied such charges, claiming they provide
only moral support.
   Cristiani praised a Central American initiative aimed at
negotiating peaceful solutions to conflicts in Nicaragua and El
Salvador. The accords call for demobilizing the Nicaraguan rebels,
who now live in border camps in neighboring Honduras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
