<FIRST>r a AM-LinaresArrested     06-03 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Linares Arrested,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father in Life-Support Case Arrested in Traffic Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CICERO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who disconnected his comatose son from
a life-support system while holding hospital staffers at gunpoint
six weeks ago was arrested for drunken driving early Saturday,
officials said.
   Rudy Linares, 23, was released on $300 bond after his arrest in
this Chicago suburb, police said.
   The arrest came two days after Linares was treated at a hospital
for suffering a violent reaction to an illegal drug.
   He was charged with driving while intoxicated, driving on a
suspended license and driving the wrong way on a one-way street,
said police Sgt. Jerry Erjavec.
   Linares checked himself into a 28-day alcohol detoxification
program at Mac Neal Memorial Hospital in nearby Berwyn, said his
attorney, Daniel Coyne.
   ``He's very relieved,'' Coyne said. ``He feels that by signing
himself in here, a great weight has been lifted from his
shoulders.''
   Linares drew national attention in April when he pulled a gun at
a Chicago hospital and held staff members at bay while he unhooked
his 15-month-old son from a life-support system.
   Linares, a Cicero house painter with two other children, cradled
the boy in his arms until he was sure the youngster died.
   The child had been in an irreversible coma since choking on a
balloon nine months earlier. Hospital officials had refused to
unhook him from life support despite the family's requests, citing
the possibility of prosecution.
   Linares was charged with murder, but a grand jury refused to
indict him and prosecutors decided not to pursue the charge. He
pleaded guilty May 18 to a misdemeanor weapons charge and was
released on condition he receive a psychological evaluation and be
treated if authorities recommended it.
   On Thursday, Linares was taken to Mac Neal after suffering a
violent reaction to PCP, an illegal drug also known as angel dust.
</TEXT>
