<FIRST>r i AM-WeddingShootout     06-03 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wedding Shootout,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>29 Injured in Political Shootout at Wedding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialists pelted the daughter of a
conservative leader with garbage and rabbit skins as she arrived
for her wedding, setting off gun battles that injured at least 29
people, officials said Saturday.
   The wedding was attended by Prime Minister Edward Fenech Adami
and Deputy Prime Minister Guido de Marco, both of the conservative
Nationalist Party. They were not injured.
   The clashes occurred Friday night in the village of Zejtun, a
Socialist stronghold seven miles from Valletta on this
Mediterranean island off Sicily.
   When Rose Abdilla, daughter of the local Nationalist Party
president, arrived at the church in a two-horse open carriage,
Socialist Party backers threw garbage and rabbit skins at her.
   She rushed into the church, protected by police, while the
onlookers insulted her and her father, Paul Abdilla.
   Police called in reinforcements when the prime minister and
deputy prime minister arrived.
   At one point, the crowd tried to surge into the church, and
police fired tear gas to disperse hundreds of Socialists who had
massed by then.
   Gun battles broke out between police and people in the crowd.
Some of them shouted anti-government slogans.
   Officials said 26 police officers were injured, 10 by gunfire.
Three other people were injured.
   The crowd gathered after a newspaper reported that the prime
minister would be acting as a witness at the wedding.
   Although his party has preached reconciliation since defeating
the Socialists in general elections two years ago, Malta remains
politically polarized.
   Since the election, Zejtun has earned the nickname ``the
Republic of Zejtun'' for forbidding the Nationalists from holding a
meeting in the village.
   De Marco told a news conference that arrests had been made. He
gave no number.
   Despite the clashes, the wedding went on as planned.
</TEXT>
