<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 2104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PowderExplosion 1stLd-Writethru a0570 06-03 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Powder Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0570,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosions Rips Through New Jersey Gunpowder Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `Three of...,' to UPDATE with
quote from plant manager, brief power outage. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Salvatore
Rappa...' SUBS 12th graf pvs, ```There are...,' to UPDATE with more than
200 damage reports. ^By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROXBURY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions leveled three buildings
at a gunpowder plant Saturday, injuring at least 18 people, blowing
out windows in nearby towns and shaking houses up to 13 miles away.
   The 5 a.m. explosions at the Hercules Powder Inc. plant knocked
down trees, tore off doors and damaged many homes and about 80
percent of the businesses in this north-central New Jersey
township, about 40 miles west of New York City, officials said. The
plant makes gunpowder for military and commercial uses.
   ``There's absolutely nothing there but dirt and it doesn't even
look that there was a building there,'' said Val Mazzucca, a
witness who flew over the site in a helicopter several hours after
the blast. ``All of the trees are blown over on the sides. It looks
like Mount St. Helens.''
   Three of about 40 buildings at the 6-square-mile complex were
destroyed, four others had fire damage and several others were
partly damaged, plant manager Dick Best said. He said he did not
know the cause of the blast.
   ``It was a chain reaction,'' he said. ``I don't know how and
why.''
   About 30,000 Jersey Central Power &amp; Light customers in a 10-mile
radius of the blast site lost power for two minutes after the
blast, said Eunice Mackie, a company spokesman.
   Salvatore Rappa said he was working inside the finishing area of
the plant when he heard an explosion.
   ``All I know is that the lights flickered on and off throughout
the whole building and in about 15 seconds there was the first
explosion,'' Rappa said. ``Everyone hit the deck and there was a
major panic.''
   About 50 employees were working on the overnight shift, Best
said. There apparently were no life-threatening injuries.
   A supervisor for Dover General Hospital said 12 Hercules
employees had been brought in. Nine of them and about half a dozen
townspeople were treated and released and three employees were
admitted, with injuries ranging from back pains to a concussion.
All were in stable condition, said supervisor Barbara Treverrow.
   An explosion on Feb. 22, 1985, at the company's Sayerville
plant, about 20 miles to the southwest, killed an employee and
injured four other people.
   Best said the material that exploded Sunday was a smokeless
propellant used in shotgun shells.
   He said that to limit damage, the plant is divided into
compartments that each contain no more than 1,000 pounds of
gunpowder. The gunpowder plant is located in a somewhat isolated
area near several small towns.
   ``There are windows blown out throughout the area,'' said Sgt.
Mike Hass, of the Randolph Police Department, about three miles
from Roxbury Township. Police said they received about 200 damage
reports.
   ``We're assisting, standing by at the businesses in terms of
looting that may occur,'' Hass said.
   Roxbury Fire Chief John Ward said a fire caused by the blast was
put out by 8 a.m.
   A resident of Flanders, about five miles away from the plant,
said he was awakened by four loud explosions.
   ``It blew me right out of bed,'' said John Larson. ``At 5:05 one
went off, then three more went off. The blinds blew right out from
the window.''
   Jay Brown, who lives half a mile from the plant, said: ``We saw
the flames go up and then we heard an explosion. The first one felt
like an earthquake. The second one blew out the windows of my house
and busted the garage door right off the frame.''
   Rudy Spagnola, a State Farm Insurance Co. agent with an office
in a shopping center about a mile from the plant, said the
explosion shook the blinds at his house in Morristown 13 miles away.
   ``I'm definitely upset. Who needs this?'' Spagnola said. ``It's
lucky it wasn't a weekday.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
