<FIRST>u i AM-China-Tiananmen     06-03 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Tiananmen,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence at Tiananmen Could Leave Permanent Scar on China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke from burning vehicles cast a pall over
Tiananmen Square Sunday morning after violence that will leave a
permanent scar on China.
   The numbers of dead and wounded from military attacks on
demonstrators were estimated in the hundreds. Massive arrests are
inevitable along with purges in the Communist Party leadership.
   The military action made it clear the government was willing to
use brutal force against mainly unarmed and peaceful demonstrators
to ensure the privileges and power of an aging leadership and to
perpetuate the political system.
   Deng Xiaoping, China's 84-year-old senior leader, may have
forfeited his place as one of the 20th century's great statesmen _
his 10 years of economic reforms tarnished by his willingness to
have blood shed rather than relinquish political power.
   Premier Li Peng, who refused to meet with students and discuss
their pleas for greater democracy and instead declared martial law
in Beijing on May 20, has won the odium of millions.
   Other elder leaders who dredged up their hard-line ideologies
rather than listen to the pulse of the nation also will be known as
men who sanctioned the killings of young idealists.
   The People's Liberation Army betrayed the chants of the students
that ``the people's army loves the people'' _ reflecting the
respect many Chinese had for the army until Sunday morning.
   The crushing of the protests reaffirmed Deng's philosophy that
political stability is crucial for economic modernization and
social unrest is intolerable.
   But his quest for stability may be in jeopardy. Military force
will not quiet the resentment of official corruption expressed by
the students at Tiananmen.
   Troops in the streets may drive anti-government and anti-party
expressions underground for a while but they cannot eradicate them.
   Student leaders, referring to government suppression, spoke of a
``long winter'' coming that will affect the nation's faltering
economic plans.
   With the government divided and weakened by strife, problems of
inflation, unemployment and labor unrest will be unattended.
   If the conservatives push through their purge of Communist Party
chief Zhao Ziyang and other moderates who opposed the crackdown,
China could be deprived of a generation of creative and progressive
thinkers.
   The flow of desperately needed foreign investments will suffer
because of the political crisis. Tourism will decline.
   China and the United States, long at odds over human rights
issues, could be heading for cooler relations that will involve
U.S. willingness to provide technology and economic assistance.
   President Bush said Saturday he deeply deplored the decision to
use force ``against peaceful demonstrators and the consequent loss
of life.''
   Chinese leaders often note China's 4,000-year history and say
the Chinese have the wisdom and patience to outlast crises of the
moment.
   But Chinese observing the rapid changes in the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe will not be satisfied with reciting catechisms of
communism and the evils of bourgeois liberalization.
   Chinese need only look back at the last Tiananmen Incident on
April 5, 1976, to note that violence can destroy those who initiate
it.
   On that date a radical clique seeking to cement its power
ordered out military units that killed about 100 people who had
gone to the square to mourn the late Premier Chou En-lai. Horror
and anger at the killings led to events that brought about the
downfall of the radicals six months later and the emergence of Deng
Xiaoping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
