<HEAD>Li Peng Comments on `Bright' Prospects for Environment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores cycle designator, SUBS lead to CORRECT `Saturday' to
`Sunday'; SUBS grafs 6-7, bgn, ```The prospects...,' to to clarify that
broadcast was Saturday, include that grammatical error was made in recorded
translation. ^With AM-China, Bjt, and AM-Common Future, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese PremierLi Peng, in a statement taped
before Sunday's bloody crackdown in Beijing, pledged China to work
to improve the world environment and concluded that the prospects
for people are ``bright.''
   Li, dressed in a Western-style suit, recorded the statement for
a global television broadcast from New York called ``Our Common
Future,'' which was intended to raise environmental consciousness.
   ``Human beings are now facing challenges from the gradual
warming of the climate on the global scale,'' Li said in Chinese.
``To curb the development of the tendency requires common efforts
by many countries and the whole world as well.''
   ``China, as a member of the international community, will
steadfastly honor its commitments,'' he said. ``I believe that
advanced countries should take more responsibility for
environmental problems and should make a higher commitment.''
   ``The prospects for human beings is bright,'' he concluded in
the recorded translation.
   The celebrity-filled broadcast Saturday, aimed at more than 1
billion people, was picked up satellite feeds from London, Moscow,
Australia, Brazil, Tokyo, Poland and elsewhere.
   Li recorded the statement before Chinese troops stormed
Tiananmen Square on Sunday to remove pro-democracy demonstrators
occupying it. Hundreds were killed and injured.
