<FIRST>r a AM-PipelineSpill     06-03 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pipeline Spill,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pipeline Spews 13,200 Gallons of Oil Into River in Colorado</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRAIG, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ruptured pipeline spilled about 13,200
gallons of crude oil into the Yampa River, home to two endangered
species of fish, officials said.
   The Amoco Pipeline Co. line near here broke open early Friday,
said Moffat County Sheriff Jeff Corriveau. It was discovered when
an oil slick was spotted on the Yampa three miles below the point
where the pipe crosses the northwestern Colorado river.
   Amoco officials immediately turned off the pumps to the 6-inch
diameter line, stopping the flow of oil within a few hours, said
Jerry White, the company's area manager in Casper, Wyo.
   Amoco officials estimated that about 300 barrels, or about
13,200 gallons, spilled into the river. Crews were immediately
dispatched to throw oil-collection booms across the river.
   ``The spill is in the No. 1 area for the Colorado squawfish,''
which is endangered, said state Fish and Wildlife Service biologist
Harold Tyus. ``In the next few weeks, the squawfish will be in the
peak of their spawning season.''
   The endangered humpback chub also swims in the Yampa, as do game
fish such as pike, trout and catfish.
   The 106-mile pipeline links an oilfield near Craig with storage
tanks near Wamsutter in south central Wyoming. It was built 45
years ago, and rebuilt in 1986, and is pipeline is buried 3 feet
underground.
   ``I don't think there's any suggestion of sabotage, but we're
investigating and cleaning up at the same time,'' White said.
   The oil, traveling downstream at about 4 mph, is expected to
reach the Yampa's confluence with the Green River late Saturday or
early Sunday, Jim Knoy of the U.S. Environmental Protection
Administration's Denver office said Saturday.
   The oil will have to pass through rapids, which will help break
it up, Knoy said.
   Knoy said that if Amoco's estimate of the spill's size was
correct, no long-term cleanup will be needed.
   The cause of the rupture was being investigated, officials said.
</TEXT>
