<HEAD>Jackson to Move to Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, considered a potential
candidate for mayor of Washington, said Saturday night that he
intends to move into a home he owns in the District of Columbia
once renovations are completed.
   But Jackson said in a telephone interview from Chicago that he
had not made any decision on whether he make the capital his legal
voting residence _ a move he would be required to make by November
if he is to become a candiate for mayor in the city's 1990
elections.
   Jackson will probably move into the house in August or
September, said a source close to Jackson, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Jackson, a long-time Chicago resident, purchased a home in the
district four years ago, but it has remained vacant and in need of
substantial repairs. Jackson began renovation work on the home this
year.
   Asked if he intends to move into the home when the work is
finished, Jackson said, ``Of course, yes.''
   Asked if he intends to make it his legal residence and to
register to vote in the city, Jackson answered, ``we have not made
such a decision.''
   Jackson has said repeatedly that he is in Washington several
times a week and he wants to live in the house rather than stay at
a hotel.
   Washington Mayor Marion S. Barry has the object of criminal
investigations involving drugs and has been beset by a series of
embarrassing disclosures about his personal life.
   A federal grand jury is investigating Barry's repeated visits to
the Washington hotel room of a man, Charles Lewis, who was later
convicted on drug charges in the Virgins Islands. Lewis faces more
charges here.
   Barry is completing his third term and is considering seeking
another term.
   Jackson and Barry are long-time friends from the civil rights
battles of the 1960s, and Jackson has said he would not run against
Barry for the mayoral position. But Jackson has declined to say
what he will do if Barry declines to run for a fourth term, as some
Barry advisers have urged.
   Jackson's Rainbow Coalition organization plans to expand its
Washington offices and establish most of its political and lobbying
operations in the city, a source in the organization said.
   Jackson hasn't decided whether to make Washington or Chicago the
principal headquarters of the organization, said the source,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
