<FIRST>r a AM-SHOilScam     06-03 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SH Oil Scam,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>$20 Million Con Man Receives Stiff Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of bilking hundreds of people
of $20 million through a pyramid scheme received a 15-year prison
sentence with an unusual 10-year probation, but promised investors
they'd get their money back.
   Authorities, however, said the reimbursement plan that Stephen
L. Smith proposed Friday was just another attempt to mislead
investors in his SH Oil and Gas Exploration company.
   Circuit Judge J. Tim Strickland in Bartow sentenced Smith on
Wednesday to 15 years in prison, and banned him from owning an
expensive home, driving an exotic automobile or doing consulting
work for 10 years after his release.
   Smith, 38, will also be prohibited from making more than $30,000
a year during the probation, and must give lectures on the evils of
white-collar crime at colleges and high schools.
   Smith, who has also been sentenced to 10 years behind bars on
federal bank fraud violations, could be released from prison after
four years.
   His attorney, Montjoy Trimble of Lexington, Ky., said he would
appeal Strickland's probation sentence.
   Smith pleaded guilty in March to 98 state felony charges. He was
accused of cheating about 700 investors out of $20 million between
1979 and 1987 through a $125 million pyramid scheme.
   A creditors meeting at bankruptcy court in Tampa on Friday
marked the first time that Smith answered questions from both
investors and investigators since the state closed SH Oil in
December 1987.
   Smith promised 50 investors who attended that he would provide a
reimbursement plan to ``handle any and all alleged shortfalls
you've had since SH Oil was closed.''
   Smith didn't elaborate on the plan during the meeting, but said
it was designed to refund lost investments within 10 to 15 years.
   He said the plan would pay investors $1 to $1.5 million annually
for nine to 14 years, then pay them a lump sum of $11.5 million to
$18 million in 10th or 15th year.
   Attorney Allan Watkins, hired to help SH Oil's federal trustee,
called Smith's plan ``Ouija board'' economics.
   Terry Smith, the trustee administering $10 million to $15
million worth of seized SH Oil assets, said the reimbursement plan
is ``taking assets and playing investment games with them.''
   ``I say just give the money back to creditors and let them
manage their own money,'' Terry Smith said.
   Stephen Smith filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy Feb. 24. He claimed
assets of about $15 million and liabilities of about $250 million.
   Smith, who remains free on $350,000 in state and federal bonds,
is scheduled to report to Saufley federal prison near Pensacola on
Wednesday, his attorney said.
</TEXT>
