<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 2331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AIDS-International     06-03 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-International,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Workers Say Prostitution and Prejudice Hindering AIDS Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aids, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prostitution and prejudice against homosexuals
are hindering efforts to control the spread of AIDS in developing
countries, a group of international health workers said Saturday.
   They spoke in Montreal, where the Fifth International Conference
on AIDS opens Sunday and 12,000 delegates are expected to attend.
   Prostitution has been a major factor in the ``wildfire-like
spread of AIDS through Central Africa,'' said Chandra Mouli, head
of an AIDS education project in Zambia.
   ``Because of high levels of unemployment ... young women often
have no practical alternatives to prostitution.''
   The World Health Organization has received reports of 23,000
cases of AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, in Africa
but many cases are not reported and the figure is believed to be
closer to 100,000.
   Poverty also has contributed to the large numbers of male
prostitutes in Thailand, according to Natee Teerarojjanapongs, a
Thai specialist.
   He said there have been few attempts to educate Thailand's
homosexuals and test them for the presence of the virus of the
deadly disease.
   Norma Kaminsky, a Costa Rican community health worker, said that
in Latin American countries most AIDS victims have been homosexual
men and hemophiliacs.
   Central and South American countries have reported 11,000 AIDS
cases to the World Health Organization. The number of AIDS victims
in the United States is nearing 100,000.
   Ms. Kaminsky said poor relations between police and Latin
American homosexual communities have hampered the detection and
prevention of AIDS.
   ``Lack of trust in the authorities has been a major obstacle,''
she said. ``Homosexuality has been repressed by the police, gay
bars have been closed and gays have been pursued.''
   A government-sponsored television campaign in Chile to educate
the public about AIDS encountered strong social opposition, said
Alonso de la Carrera, a Santiago-based health worker.
   When the messages were broadcast in March following long delays,
they were aimed exclusively at the heterosexual population and
contained no concrete information on prevention of AIDS, he said.
   African governments are struggling to control the AIDS epidemic,
the health workers from that continent said.
   A study in the Kagera region of northwestern Tanzania found
4,000 orphans were AIDS carriers, said Dr. F.J. Owenya, a Red Cross
worker.
   He said that in addition to prostitution in the region, the
common practice of sharing of unsterilized instruments such as
razor blades and safety pins to pierce ears has contributed to the
spread of AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
