<FIRST>r a AM-HostageWife     06-03 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Wife,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceremony Marks Sutherland's Fourth Year Of Captivity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of hostage Thomas Sutherland
continued a ``personal odyssey'' into her husband's past Friday to
mark the end of his fourth year of captivity in Lebanon.
   ``It's very, very special for me to be here,'' said Jean
Sutherland at an outdoor ceremony on the campus at Iowa State
University, where she met and married Thomas Sutherland when both
were students in the 1950s.
   Mrs. Sutherland arrived in Ames from Scotland, where she had
visited the farm of her husband's family. On June 9, she will
participate in a ceremony for her husband at Colorado State
University in Fort Collins, Colo., where the couple taught before
leaving for American University in Beirut.
   ``We went as a team, and we are still there as a team, and we
are still working together,'' said Mrs. Sutherland.
   She has continued teaching at American University since her
husband's abduction on June 9, 1985. Sutherland was dean of
agriculture at the school.
   ``I'm doing a personal odyssey for Tom _ to go to Tom's sources
and gather a vitality and strength that I can take back to
Beirut,'' Mrs. Sutherland, 55, told a crowd of about 40 people
gathered under the bell tower at the center of the Iowa State
campus.
   After the ceremony, the school's bell tolled 48 times _ once for
each month Sutherland has been held hostage.
   ``I will take this back to American University and we will get
it into the newspaper so that Tom will know he has this lifeline,''
said Mrs. Sutherland.
   She spoke in front of a grove of trees tied with yellow ribbons.
Beside her was a banner with her husband's picture and the words,
``We have not forgotten.''
   She said she harbors no bitterness toward the U.S. government,
which has been unable to obtain the release of Sutherland or eight
other Americans held hostage in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press. Anderson, also an Iowa State graduate, was captured March
16, 1985.
   Mrs. Sutherland said she hopes the Bush administration can make
progress that Ronald Reagan was unable to accomplish as president.
   ``We have a chance to do something with the new
administration,'' she said.
   ``We hope that Tom will be out before the next year elapses,''
said Mrs. Sutherland's father, William G. Murray of Ames.
   John Anderson, interim director of university relations at Iowa
State, presented Mrs. Sutherland with a book containing signatures
of Iowa State students, faculty and other Iowans urging the release
of Sutherland and the other hostages.
   ``We hope that it can get to Tom to show that there is solid and
broad-based support for him and the others in Beirut,'' Anderson
told her. ``We pledge to continue these observances for as long as
they're necessary.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
