<FIRST>r i AM-Prague-Dissent     06-03 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prague-Dissent,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>^Police in Czechoslovakia Break Up Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in Czechoslovakia broke up a
meeting of the Movement for Civil Freedom and detained about 70
people who were attending but released them all after questioning,
a rights activist said Friday.
   Activist Petr Uhl, who was reached in Prague, capital of
Czechoslovakia, by telephone, said uniformed and plainclothes
police entered about 20 minutes after the meeting began in a Prague
restaurant on Thursday, made identity checks and took away
participants for questioning.
   Uhl, who did not attend, said two participants, Ladislav Lis and
Rudolf Battek, refused to leave voluntarily and were removed by
force. All those questioned were back home after about two hours.
   The Movement, a non-conformist group formed last October, calls
for political pluralism and a return to private ownership.
   Uhl said that he, Jan Urban, Sasha Vondra and Milan Simecka were
invited by the Vienna-based Helsinki Federation of Human Rights to
go to Paris for the current Conference on the Human Dimension, but
they have not received travel documents.
   Vondra is a spokesman for the Charter 77 human rights group.
</TEXT>
