<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0618 06-03 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Killed in Attacks; Kidnapped Engineers Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs UPDATING with engineers freed. Picks up 2nd
graf, The Rev. ... with minor editing; ADDS 6 grafs details, background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Roman Catholic priest,
two policemen and four civilians in separate attacks, and police
said Friday they increased security for Colombia's police chief
after learning he is on a drug cartel's assassination list.
   Also Friday, leftist guerrillas freed four engineers of the
Brazilian state oil company Petrobras who were kidnapped in
Colombia and held 43 days in the tropical interior, a company
official said.
   The Rev. Sergio Restrepo was killed Thursday by unidentified
gunmen near Tierralta, about 280 miles north of Bogota in an area
where guerrillas are active, authorities said. Police had no motive
for the slaying.
   Late Thursday, in the western city of Pereira, armed men entered
a restaurant and sprayed it with gunfire, killing two men and two
women and wounding six people, police said.
   Pereira is capital of the coffee-growing state of Risarlda.
Risarlda's governor, Diego Patino, and two aides left the
restaurant minutes before the attack, but police said the attack
apparently was not directed at them.
   Early Friday, two policemen were shot to death near Anoril,
about 200 miles north of Bogota, in an apparent guerrilla ambush.
   Meanwhile, authorities in Bogota said they were strengthening
security for the national police chief, Gen. Miguel Gomez Padilla,
and Gen. Rafael Munoz, chief of the police force's anti-narcotics
division, after discovering they were on an assassination list of
the feared Medellin cartel of cocaine traffickers.
   The existence of the list was disclosed by Padilla, who said it
also listed the head of the security police, Gen. Miguel Maza
Marquez, who escaped a car-bomb assassination attempt Tuesday that
left six dead and about 30 wounded.
   Colombia has been plagued for years by violence carried out by
drug traffickers, right-wing vigilantes and leftist guerrilla
groups.
   Jose Ferndandez, manager of Colombian operations for Petrobras,
said in an interview broadcast by the national radio network RCN
that no ransom was paid for the kidnapped engineers' release
Friday. He spoke in Bucaramanaga.
   Fernandez said political issues were discussed in negotiations
with the captors, the pro-Cuban National Liberation Army.
   The engineers _ three Brazilians and a Colombian _ were handed
over to Brazilian labor union officials who had been trying to
obtain the men's freedom.
   Guerrillas seized the four during an April 20 attack on an oil
drilling site near Barancabermeja, 170 miles northeast of Bogota.
   It was part of a guerrilla campaign to pressure the governmment
into nationalizing Colombia's petroleum industry. The group this
year also has kidnapped mayors, congressmen, other politicians and
oil company workers, all of them freed after the captors expounded
on their opposition to private and foreign investment in oil.
   The guerrillas also have regularly bombed important oil
pipelines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
