<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     06-03 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0819</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party struggling to keep
itself and Poland's economy afloat is competing against an
invigorated Solidarity slate of candidates in an election seen as
the freest in Eastern Europe in four decades.
   The elections Sunday for seats in the current one-house
parliament and a new Senate are also viewed as a huge gamble for
both sides.
   About 80 percent of Poland's 27 million eligible voters are
expected to vote.
   Campaigning ended Friday with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa
taping a television message and Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, the
Polish leader, delivering a rare television address.
   Walesa urged restraint on both sides and said many people in the
government were worried about the election's outcome. Jaruzelski
made a similar appeal for restraint.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voluntary decision by Alar's
manufacturer to take the chemical off the U.S. market drew praise
from the nation's apple belt as the best way to win back consumers.
   Uniroyal Chemical Co. continued to defend the chemical as safe,
but said Friday that continued use on apples raised public doubts
about the safety of America's food supply. The chemical has been
labeled a possible carcinogen, although tests are continuing.
   ``We should be hopeful and expect this will be the beginning of
restoring consumer confidence,'' said John McAlister, a spokesman
for Selah-based Tree Top Inc., the nation's largest apple juice
maker.
   But other industry figures said the action is unlikely to help
the current crop, which has turned into a financial disaster.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government watchdog says $1.6 trillion in
private pension funds are subject to potential fraud and abuse
because of loose regulations and lax enforcement of federal pension
laws.
   Labor Department Inspector General J. Brian Hyland said in a
report to Congress on Friday that the problems that leave the
pension system open to abuse are much like those that triggered the
savings and loan crisis.
   Unless Congress acts quickly to strengthen the laws and require
the government to improve oversight of pension funds the potential
exists for a ``nightmare'' that would dwarf the S&amp;L crisis, Hyland
said in the report.
   ``As, unfortunately, has been demonstrated by the recent savings
and loan crisis, government regulation of an industry does not
ensure that invested assets are protected,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he brought a
``message of hope'' back from his triumphant weeklong trip to
Europe but says he doesn't expect Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to respond soon to arms control initiatives embraced by
NATO nations.
   ``There's no grand design out there right now now. We just want
to move forward,'' Bush told reporters.
   Bush was spending a quiet weekend at his family's oceanside home
before returning to Washington on Sunday.
   At an arrival ceremony at nearby Pease Air Force Base in
Portsmouth, N.H., on Friday, Bush declared: ``We must stay on the
offensive. We must now get to work to end the cold war.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man likely to succeed Jim Wright as
House speaker believes both parties are tired of partisan
mudslinging and is pledging to use his ties to Democrats and
Republicans to improve the atmosphere in Congress.
   Rep. Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., spoke critically Friday of the
ethics war sweeping Congress in recent months. But Foley, known as
a consensus builder, also praised the work of the House Ethics
Committee, which comprises six Democrats and six Republicans.
   ``The committee has won a broad degree of public respect in the
manner in which it's handled the difficult issues before it,''
Foley said. ``What we are talking about is the use of ethics issues
as a tool or instrument of recrimination, partisanship.
   ``It's not the ethics committee, it's the members on either side
who are trying to come up with some concept of abusive charges.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With much fanfare, authorities Sunday are opening
a seven-mile stretch of Interstate 90 that has the dubious
distinction of being the most expensive segment of freeway ever
built.
   It is part of a $1.46 billion highway project for the
mushrooming Seattle metropolis to build roads that probably will be
badly congested by the time they are completed in 1994.
   For the time being, the new link between Seattle and Bellevue
across Lake Washington brings welcome relief from the twice-daily
creep across the lake's two existing four-lane spans that become
jammed by fender-benders.
   Commuters also say goodbye to an infamous I-90 lane that
switched direction depending on the commute. With no barrier to
separate traffic, motorists tagged it the ``death lane.''
   At about $200 million a mile, the freeway has set a record for
costliness.
</TEXT>
