<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     06-03 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0866</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy cooled slightly in May for the
first time since July 1986, in a further indication inflation could
be easing, the nation's purchasing managers said in their monthly
report.
   Production by the nation's factories continued to grow, although
at a significantly slower pace than in April, according to the
report issued by the National Association of Purchasing Management.
   ``The total economy resumed its ratcheting path toward slower
growth during May as the manufacturing economy reported the first
decline in growth in almost three years,'' Robert J. Bretz,
chairman of the trade group, said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment slipped to 5.2 percent last month
while job growth sputtered to a three-year low, the government said.
   The Labor Department said Friday that civilian joblessness fell
from April's rate of 5.3 percent, with a decline in the number of
people looking for work offsetting an anemic expansion of non-farm
payrolls.
   Financial markets reacted favorably to the report, which
immediately renewed speculation among economists over whether the
Federal Reserve is ready to relax its tight hold on credit in the
face of a slowing economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $1.6 trillion in pension funds
potentially are at risk because of poor regulations and inept
enforcement of federal laws, the Labor Department's inspector
general said.
   J. Brian Hyland urged Congress on Friday to immediately
investigate potential abuses and shortfalls of federal pension laws.
   The report came under attack from a group involved in pension
policy and from the Labor Department itself, which critized
Hyland's comparison of pension funding and the S&amp;L crisis and said
a number of initiatives designed to improve enforcement of pension
laws were under way.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary of agriculture authorized
additional limited relief for livestock producers with parched
pastures, and an Iowa cattlemen's group said that it was pleased
even if there were more strings attached than it desired.
   While Friday's decision applies to 16 states with stunted
pastures and meager feed supplies, the U.S. Department of
Agriculture said the relief is needed most in Iowa, Kansas and
Nebraska.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturer of Alar, the apple chemical
that stirred a national furor over a possible cancer risk to
children, said it is taking the substance off the U.S. market
immediately.
   Uniroyal Chemical Co. continued to defend the chemical as safe
but said Friday that continued use on apples ``is causing doubt and
confusion about the safety of America's food supply.''
   Apple growers and processors had pleaded for such action because
fears about Alar had drastically cut into apple industry sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If new USX Corp. Chairman Charles A. Corry
thought his predecessor's troubles with takeover speculator Carl
Icahn were history, he got a jarring reminder less than 48 hours
after taking charge of the steel and energy giant.
   Icahn's sale of a record $2 billion block of Texaco Corp. stock
on Thursday immediately raised speculation that he might turn his
attention to USX, which he unsuccessfully pursued in 1987.
   Corry, who succeeded retiring Chairman David M. Roderick on
Wednesday, declined comment at a news conference Friday on the
possible impact of Icahn's stock sale.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-crippled Eastern Airlines said it was
requiring non-union employees to work more hours for the same pay,
cutting management salaries by 20 percent and eliminating vacations
for the rest of the year.
   The austerity measures were announced Friday as a federal
bankruptcy judge in New York kept alive hopes by striking employees
that the sickly airline might be purchased by a friendly investor
they are backing with their own money.
   At a hearing, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland gave the
investor group led by Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie
until 2 p.m. EDT Monday to further refine a revised buyout proposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. paid the government $5 million, one
of the stiffest civil penalties ever levied by federal officials,
as settlement for the deliberate destruction of 1 billion cubic
feet of natural gas.
   Tenneco said Friday the incident involved about 1.17 billion
cubic feet of gas over about a nine-month period ending Feb. 3,
1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno will continue existing
policies toward the United States and other countries, and will not
ease his tough response to U.S. trade actions against Japan,
officials said.
   Parliament chose Uno, 66, as the prime minister Friday and he
promised political reforms to avoid a recurrence of the Recruit
bribery scandal, which forced the resignation of Noboru Takeshita.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market swept ahead to new post-crash highs Friday,
sending the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials up 27.20 to
2,517.83.
   The dollar fell sharply.
   Long-term interest rates plunged to their lowest levels in 15
months, and bond prices surged.
   Gold and silver futures prices surged; grain, soybean and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
